<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State employees wo n't be dialing for dollars any longer after their attempts to cash in on a $ 1,000 radio call-in contest brought the Capitol's telephone system to a crashing halt. `` I guess the economy is so bad in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> that everybody is trying to get money,'' <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Stringfellow </PERSON>, state director of telecommunications, said Tuesday. `` But you should n't be using state phones to be calling on to radio contests.'' Officials reset the phone system to prevent any calls to the exchange set aside for radio call-in contests after service was disrupted several times, <PERSON> Stringfellow </PERSON> said. `` We thought we had just had an equipment failure,'' he said. `` But the second time it went down one of our employees suggested it was at the same time as one of the radio contests.'' Officials discovered the phone failure occurred within a minute of the start of a contest by a local radio station offering a $ 1,000 prize. The Capitol phone system has about 14,000 lines, and its usual capacity is about 2,000 calls at any time. But the radio contest bumped the phone traffic up to 8,000 calls, <PERSON> Stringfellow </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forget about toga parties. <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students have come up with something more relevant for the 1980s and this presidential year _ the Pledge party. As in Pledge of Allegiance, of course. Police were responding for the second time to noise complaints about a party at a student's house when <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> junior <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBoeuf </PERSON> led 150 to 200 revelers in the Pledge. `` I thought it'd be funny,'' said <PERSON> LeBoeuf </PERSON>, who led the group from a trough containing beer kegs and ice. `` What are the police going to do with 200 people standing around saying the pledge _ arrest them for being patriotic?'' No, but they did cite host Kimberly A. Mart for violating the city's noise ordinance after the patriotic partyers pushed police noise meters over the town's 70-decibel limit. The citation, the second given for the Sept. 10 party, could cost Mart $ 128. She was scheduled to appear in court on Tuesday for the misdemeanor violation. `` The officers were kind of laughing when they took the meter reading,'' said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 21, who lives at the house. `` People were n't saying it in any hostile way. They had smiles on their faces and some had hands over their hearts. No big deal, we thought.''
