<HEAD>Leading Mafia Investigator Agrees to Stay On</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s top Mafia investigator has withdrawn his resignation, alleviating a crisis in the country's war on organized crime. <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON>, an investigating magistrate in the Sicilian capital of <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION>, had charged when he offered his resignation July 30 that Mafia investigations were obstructed. He also said his methods `` differ radically'' from those of his superior, <PERSON> Antonino </PERSON> <PERSON> Meli </PERSON>, who was appointed chief investigating magistrate of the anti-Mafia judicial `` pool'' in February. <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> asked for a transfer and the other members of the pool then announced their resignations. A former colleague of <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> charged in July that <PERSON> Meli </PERSON> was weakening the pool by assigning its judges non-Mafia cases and sending Mafia cases to investigators outside the pool. <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> told judicial officials Wednesday that he was staying on `` in conformance with the ruling'' last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magistrates </ORGANIZATION>, the national judicial watchdog that appointed <PERSON> Meli </PERSON>. The council, praising the pool's work, found that <PERSON> Meli </PERSON> did not divert cases and called on <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> not to quit. Magistrates in the pool, especially <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON>, have been credited for some of the country's biggest successes against organized crime, including the `` maxi'' anti-Mafia trial that ended in December with 338 convictions. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities say <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> provided critical help in investigations such as the one leading to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trial of suspects in the case of the `` Pizza Connection,'' which discovered that pizza parlors in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> were used as fronts for heroin dealing.
