<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Harvest     09-22 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Harvest,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Izvestia Says Grain Harvest Down This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s grain harvest this year will be smaller than the relatively good harvests of the two previous years because of drought in the country's breadbasket, <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> reported. The Soviet government newspaper gave no figures, but said the harvest was just drawing to a close and it was clear it would fall short of the 231 million tons harvested in each of the past two years. A significant shortfall in the grain harvest would be a blow to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s efforts to improve food supplies to consumers and reform agriculture. It also would require the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to use more of its scare foreign currency to buy grain instead of machinery and equipment to modernize the economy. `` The summer drought has inflicted an appreciable blow on the principle grainaries of the country _ the <LOCATION> Volga </LOCATION> region, the Urals, western <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said in the report Wednesday. It said experts of the government's giant agro-industrial complex had determined `` the grain procurements as a whole around the country will be somewhat lower than the level of the two previous years.'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said that although it was reporting bad news, it was a sign of progress in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> society that the news about such a sensitive area of Soviet life could be reported at all. Last year's harvest was considered by Western observers to be good because the growing season was unusually damp and cool. Figures for 1986 and 1987 were well above the average for 1981-1985 of about 203.5 million tons but well below official targets, which Western observers consider unrealistic. The 1986 target was 255 million tons, and Soviet officials are trying to boost that to 275 million tons over several years' time. Western experts say the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> uses about 240-255 million tons of grain a year and must import what it can not produce. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is trying to reform Soviet agriculture by giving families and small brigades of farm workers more responsibility and greater security on the huge state and collective farms. The Soviet leader hopes to encourage farmers to work harder by offering them a chance to earn more money and live better.
