<HEAD>Hungary Opens Up To Capitalist World</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is performing a delicate balancing act between East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> as it opens its doors to the business and technology of the capitalist world. <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> has extended a diplomatic hand to many nations the rest of the <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> keeps at a distance. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is the first <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc nation that is to normalize diplomatic ties with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The announcement was made in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> on Sept. 13, but no date has been set. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Istvan </PERSON> <PERSON> Komoroczki </PERSON> said the move was `` in harmony with a Hungarian drive to openness to the world, irrespective of social systems. In the same week, <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> also became the first Eastern bloc nation to agree to resume diplomatic ties with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, severed after the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. After a private visit to <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> Sept. 14-15, Israeli Premier <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, the first <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> head of goverment to visit <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would renew full diplomatic ties with <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> `` in the near future.'' No date was set. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> became party boss in May and immediately embarked on a series of trips to the West, including visits to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The communist leader has emphasized <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s need for Western techn