ON> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> hit an all-time low this summer in the wake of <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>'s alleged discrimination against its 1.7 million minority Hungarians, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> on Aug. 28. The Hungarian leader drew criticism at home for his failure to persuade the Romanian government to scrap its plan to raze thousands of villages inhabited by the Hungarian minority. A Western analyst in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, with its good human rights record and liberal policies, has presented itself to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> as `` user-friendly.'' At the same time, <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> seems to have <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s approval in pursuing whatever foreign policy it chooses _ as long as they do n't damage its ties to the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact alliance This independence began long before <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, but it received a boost when the two leaders came to power. In 1985, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> was the East bloc host of a 35-nation cultural forum under the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> human rights accords. In March 1987, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> became the first East bloc country to join the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> in backing a minority rights resolution at the <ORGANIZATION> Vienna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. More recently, <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> was the site Aug. 30-31 of a closed-door meeting of arms experts from <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact, and it has offered to host a Soviet-U.S. summit. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s joint bid with <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> to host the 1995 World's Fair in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> and <