<FIRST>r w PM-DeltaCrash     09-22 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Delta Crash,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta Crash Investigations Study Tapes for Sound of Flap Settings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators of last month's <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> crash in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> are trying to determine whether several `` click'' sounds on the jet's cockpit voice recorder are indications the flight crew set the flaps before takeoff. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 crashed seconds after taking off from the <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> airport Aug. 31, killing 14 of the 108 people aboard. The investigation has focused on whether a false flap setting may have kept the plane from gaining altitude. At least two clicks can be heard on the recording, according to sources close to the investigation. But additional sounds also are being studied to determine the exact number of clicks and whether they relate directly to the flaps' position. The flaps, which provide an aircraft with lift during takeoff, were supposed to have been set at 15 degrees for proper takeoff of Flight 1141. The Dallas Morning News on Wednesday quoted <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> officials it did not name as saying they were studying the possibility that the flaps were extended, but not far enough. `` What you hear -LRB- on the tape of the cockpit conversation -RRB- are two ` clicks' in quick succession. That means that the flaps were at least at the 5-degree setting,'' the newspaper quoted one source as saying. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 has flap settings of 2, 5 and 15 degrees. The flap control mechanism in the cockpit has notches that produce clicking sounds as the lever is moved. Meanwhile, investigators are expected to conduct tests in flight simulators to determine what minimum flap setting would have been required for the plane to gain proper lift. Some aviation experts who have followed the accident investigation say the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727, which was not fully loaded, should have been able to take off even with a lower than optimum flap setting. <PERSON> Drucella </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday the safety board would have no comment on what investigators are examining on the cockpit voice recorder tapes. Investigators have uncovered conflicting evidence as to the jet's flap setting at the time of takeoff. The voice recorder shows the co-pilot acknowledged having set the flaps to 15 degrees during the routine preflight checklist. `` Fifteen, fifteen, green,'' the co-pilot was heard to say on the cockpit recorder tape, according to sources involved in the investigation. One source suggested that the co-pilot, if he set the flaps, probably did so earlier and was reading off the flap setting at the time his response was recorded. The reference to `` green'' refers to a light showing the position of separate control surfaces on the forward edge of the wings called slats. A green light shows them to be in the extended position. Slats also are supposed to be extended during takeoff, but investigators have said they found the slats on the wrecked aircraft in an unlocked but retracted position. Investigators have said the jack screws on the wings also indicated the flaps were in a retracted position and the flap-slat control lever in the cockpit was found in an up position, indicating the flaps were retracted. The co-pilot who was responsible for setting the flaps has told investigators he can not remember anything after the aircraft was pushed back from the gates.
