 In an unusual meeting of the financial district and the red light district, an investor group plans a stock offering to raise money to buy the <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's biggest legal bordello. The group, led by <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> and real estate developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Clough </PERSON>, plans to raise $ 23.3 million through a stock offering to purchase the famed brothel 10 miles east of here, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said. The group filed an application Friday with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to sell 1.165 million common shares of <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> at $ 20 a share, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said Wednesday. This is the second attempted share offering to raise money to buy the Mustang Ranch. A proposed $ 18 million sale by another group fell through in 1985 when it failed to attract enough investor interest. `` We've got everything in motion now and are just waiting to see what the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> does,'' said <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, formed last year to make the transaction. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, citing <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> rules, declined to discuss details of the deal or name the other two officers besides <PERSON> Clough </PERSON> who will control more than 40 percent of the company. Documents filed with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> indicate $ 18 million would be used to buy the 105-room brothel. The remaining funds would cover capital improvements, financial reserves and administrative costs. The ranch's founder and owner, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Conforte </PERSON>, announced in July his plan to retire from the business after roughly 30 years. He needs the proceeds from the sale to pay back income taxes and penalties. `` I'm 62 years old,'' said <PERSON> Conforte </PERSON>, who was brought to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION> in 1937 by his produce-salesman father. `` I only have a few years left to live the good life and I want to enjoy them.'' <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION>'s gross revenue fell last year to $ 5.6 million from $ 5.9 million in 1986, but profits rose to $ 917,000 from $ 848,000, according to the prospectus. The prostitutes work as independent contractors, paying the ranch $ 10 a day for meals and facilities and splitting the gross receipts 50-50 with the house. The prospectus noted that the stock offering was a high-risk venture because of potential lawsuits, adverse publicity and the possibility that clients could get acquired immune deficiency syndrome. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> law requires prostitutes to be tested monthly for AIDS, and so far no working women have tested positive for the AIDS virus. The brothels also require customers to use condoms to protect against disease. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> planned to file a response to the investor group's application within 20 days listing any deficiencies If the stock offering is allowed, it would the first time a bordello has become a publicly-held corporation. <PERSON> Conforte </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> began operations at the 440-acre ranch in the late 1950s, when <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> merely tolerated prostitution. In 1971, <ORGANIZATION> Conforte </ORGANIZATION> won <LOCATION> Storey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s approval for the brothel, pioneering the statewide movement to allow prostitution in most counties. The state now has about three dozen licensed brot