<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained marginally on the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> foreign exchange market today while share prices declined sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. After opening at 134.35 yen, the dollar moved in a narrow range of 134.27-134 .55 yen in light trading It closed at 134.47 yen, up 0.29 yen from the previous day's close. Exchange dealers said the slight gain reflected strong showing of the currency in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> overnight, but the lack of fresh incentives prevented the dollar from strengthening further. `` The dollar is in a difficult position to move too far because of the upcoming Group of Seven meeting,'' said an exchange dealer in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` But market participants are expecting no major changes in the meeting, either.'' The meeting of the Group of Seven, in which foreign ministers and central bank chiefs from the seven major industrialized nations discuss international economic and fiscal policies, is scheduled on Saturday in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> said he expects the current international cooperation in fiscal policies will be maintained after that meeting. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the main index on the stock exchange, declined 284.35 points, or 1.03 percent, from Wednesday's close to finish the day's trading at 27,428.31. Securities dealers attributed the drop of share prices to profit taking. `` After the news of the Emperor's ailing health shook <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> Monday night, the general direction of the market has been negative,'' said a dealer at a major securities firm. `` So everyone is trying to take advantage of yesterday's gain.'' Despite the downward trend, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index gained 164.08 points Wedneday. Most securities dealers expect the market will remain directionless and unpredictable until Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s condition becomes clearer. `` The market as a whole appears to be regaining energy after more than a month long slump,'' said another dealer at a major securities firm, requesting anonymity. `` The increased volume and the popularity of large-capital shares are one of the signs of that.'' The volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where most major shares are listed, was 850 million shares. Both the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> foreign exchange markets will be closed Friday because of a national holiday. The stock exchange will have a half day session Saturday while foreign exchange dealing will remain closed until Monday.
