<HEAD>Five Bombs Explode In Four Cities, 38 Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty-eight people were hurt across <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in five bombings over nine hours, according to police, who said the first blast injured 18 whites, while the next-to-last hurt 19 blacks. A 1 a.m. blast today inside the Why Not disco in the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Hillbrow </LOCATION> injured 19 blacks, three seriously, and caused extensive damage, police said. The disco is frequented almost exclusively by blacks. During the Wednesday evening rush hour, a bomb exploded at the main white bus terminal in downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, injuring 19 people, all but one of them white, police said. The explosion occurred just after 5 p.m. in one of the new concrete trash bins installed throughout the city last year to muffle the effects of bombs. It shattered windows of four buses, damaged a fast-food cafe, and broke the windows of buildings and cars in the area. Meanwhile, police said early today that bombs exploded overnight in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> and in the southern towns of King <PERSON> William </PERSON>'s Town and <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION>. There were no injuries in the three attacks, police said. In <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, a bomb placed at the front door extensively damaged the home of <ORGANIZATION> Shakes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> el </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goolam </ORGANIZATION>, an <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> candidate in the municipal elections next month, police said. The explosion occurred at 1:25 a.m. In <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION>, an explosive device damaged the back of a public library and in King <PERSON> William </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Town </ORGANIZATION>, a suspected mini-limpet mine exploded in the front of the magistrate's court building. No one claimed responsibility for any of the attacks. Minister of Law and <PERSON> Order </PERSON> <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> described the blast at the bus terminal as a `` repulsive act'' carried out by `` cowards.'' There have been more than 110 bombings in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since the government declared a nationwide state of emergency in June 1986. Police have blamed virtually all the attacks on the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the main black group attempting to overthrow the white minority government. However, in recent weeks bombs have exploded at the headquarters of anti-apartheid groups and at public facilities frequented mostly by blacks. Under apartheid, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no say in national affairs.
