<SECOND>PM-Aliens-Amnesty,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Work Permits, Bars Deportation of Aliens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court has barred the deportation of up to 100,000 aliens until it decides whether the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was too restrictive in denying them amnesty. In a decision made public Wednesday, the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> also authorized temporary work permits for the aliens. The court ordered the temporary measures until it rules on whether the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> exceeded its authority by denying amnesty to aliens who had left the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> briefly. Depending on its ruling, the court could reopen the now-expired deadline for aliens to apply for amnesty under the new immigration law. The court said it would hear arguments in the case in November under an accelerated schedule. The government is appealing a federal judge's ruling in April that the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> interpreted the grounds for amnesty too narrowly. `` This is a great day for our system of justice,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Abascal </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Rural Legal Assistance lawyer in the case. He said four other federal judges around the nation have restricted <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> enforcement of related provisions of the amnesty law, but that this was the first order from an appellate court. The number of aliens potentially affected by the case is estimated to be from 50,000 to 100,000 nationwide, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON>, who represented the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>, declined comment. The new immigration law allowed aliens who have been in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> continuously since Jan. 1, 1982, to apply for amnesty by May, the first step toward legal residence. A trip outside the country that is `` brief, casual and innocent'' does not disqualify an alien from amnesty. Under an <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> interpretation, however, any departure after May 1, 1987, when amnesty applications began, that lacked advance approval from the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> could not be `` innocent'' and made the alien ineligible for amnesty. <PERSON> Abascal </PERSON> said in a statement that the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> had used its reading of the law to bar amnesty to several aliens who had made brief trips to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to see a dying relative, and to one who fell asleep in a car shortly before his friends went to <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION> for a two-hour frolic. Chief U.S. District Judge <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Karlton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> ruled in April that the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> interpretation was not authorized by the law. After finding that numerous aliens had been denied amnesty improperly or had been discouraged from applying, he issued a nationwide order in June reopening the application period through Nov. 30, which the government appealed. The appeals court decision requires that the government question any aliens arrested under the immigration law to see if they would be eligible for amnesty if not for foreign travel of the kind covered by the suit. If so, the aliens must be released without bond and given work permits while the court case is pending. The same rights must be provided to aliens who approach the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> with questions about their status and are covered by the case. <PERSON> Abascal </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> also is required to contact aliens who have been denied amnesty because of brief trips out of the country and tell them their cases are being reopened.
</TEXT>
