<HEAD>Report Faults Judge, Others For Freeing Man Who Later Killed Two,
Then Self</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man on parole for manslaughter and held for harassment was freed on $ 500 bail and allowed to commit a double murder-suicide because a judge did not take steps to discover the man's violent past, a report said. The report by <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assignment </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> also said failures by probation officers, prosecutors and family caseworkers contributed to the release of <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Vutca </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Parsippany-Troy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>. No officials will be disciplined, however, because no one was guilty of `` repeated acts'' of violating proper procedures, <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Vutca </PERSON>, a Romanian national, killed his wife, <PERSON> Dorina </PERSON>, and her mother, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Vacariu </PERSON>, on Sept. 10 at their home in Effort, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and then shot himself to death. `` Looking at the total situation, we see an incredible combination of things that went wrong,'' said <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>'s report, which was released Tuesday and submitted to state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Chief Justice <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilentz </PERSON>. `` If any one of them had gone right, the tragic consequence might have been avoided.'' <PERSON> Vutca </PERSON> was convicted of aggravated manslaughter in 1983 in the stabbing death a year earlier of his live-in girlfriend. He was paroled in 1986 and married <PERSON> Dorina </PERSON> last year. <PERSON> Vutca </PERSON> was arrested Aug. 17 on charges of harassment and violating a court order to stay away from his wife. Mrs. <PERSON> Vutca </PERSON> and her mother then moved to <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> set bail at $ 25,000 the day of the arrest. The next day, <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bangiola </PERSON>, in a routine bail-review hearing, reduced the bail to $ 5,000, or $ 500 if paid in cash. <PERSON> Vutca </PERSON> posted bail, tracked down his wife and mother-in-law and shot them to death, authorities said. <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>'s report said <PERSON> Bangiola </PERSON> did n't know about <PERSON> Vutca </PERSON>'s manslaughter conviction when he lowered bail because Ms. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>'s bail memorandum mentioning the conviction did n't arrive on his desk until the next The report also said a probation officer failed to notify the county prosecutor's office about <PERSON> Bangiola </PERSON>'s hearing, and the hearing was conducted without a prosecutor present. The report said `` many judges in Judge <PERSON> Bangiola </PERSON>'s position would have seen the $ 25,000 bail and suspected that the case must involve something more than verbal threats.'' It said <PERSON> Bangiola </PERSON> could have telephoned Ms. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> or taken other steps to find out more about <PERSON> Vutca </PERSON>'s background. <PERSON> Bangiola </PERSON> said through his secretary he would not comment on the report. <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> said judges and court employees have been `` re-educated'' about proper procedures, and that workers and the prosecutor's office have been encouraged to inform him or other judges `` when they think something has gone wrong.''
