<FIRST>r a PM-Heart-FishOil     09-22 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heart-Fish Oil,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds Fish Oil Promising Addition to Common Heart Procedure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fish oil provides the first effective way of keeping newly opened heart arteries working smoothly after angioplasty, a procedure used on 200,000 Americans annually with heart disease, according to a study published today. `` It looks very promising,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dehmer </PERSON>. `` It's the only agent so far that has even shown a hint of having an effect This study is a little like the light at the end of the tunnel.'' <PERSON> Dehmer </PERSON>, now a cardiologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>, was in charge of the fish oil experiment at the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. Angioplasty is widely used because it provides a non-surgical alternative to coronary bypass operations for people with coronary artery disease. Doctors use tiny balloons to squeeze open clogged heart arteries. A major drawback of the procedure is restenosis, the spontaneous reclosing of the newly cleared arteries. This happens in about one-third of all patients within six months of their angioplasties. When the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> doctors tested fish oil on 82 men, they found that it cut the restenosis rate by two to three times in men who were at especially high risk of this complication. Reaction from other experts was mixed. Dr. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Leaf </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, who is conducting a major study of fish oil in angioplasty, said he believes the therapy works. But Dr. <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. King III of <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> commented: `` My main concern is that a lot of small studies have made it look like restenosis was helped by so many different interventions. I would like to see bigger numbers before I buy into this.'' The study was published in today's New England Journal of Medicine. One similar recent study also found that fish oil seemed to prevent restenosis, while two others showed no effect. `` Although it's in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, it's a little premature to rush out and buy a carload of fish oil for every angioplasty patient,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Baim </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Beth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, a co-author of one of the negative studies. The researchers said they do not recommend that all angioplasty patients take fish oil, because their study was too small to be the basis of sweeping recommendations. And they said people undergoing angioplasties should not take the supplements unless they discuss it with their doctors. However, Dr. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eichhorn </PERSON>, a co-author of the study, commented, `` If I were undergoing angioplasty, the balance of potential benefits versus risks is such that I would take it myself.'' Fish oil capsules, widely available in drug and health stores, have been advertised as a way of warding off heart disease, although evidence is still skimpy. Eskimos who eat large quantities of oily fish, such as salmon, have remarkably low levels of heart disease. However, doctors disagree over whether fish oil capsules will prevent the gradual buildup of fatty deposits in the arteries, a process called atherosclerosis, that underlies heart attacks. Leaf said the latest study suggests to him that fish oil capsules may be of benefit to everyone at risk of heart disease, not just those undergoing angioplasty. `` Since angioplasty restenosis pathologically appears to be a very rapid progression of atherosclerosis, the fact that they find they can prevent restenosis suggests that fish oil will prevent coronary heart disease and heart attacks,'' Leaf said. In the latest study, half the patients took 18 capsules of MaxEPA fish oil daily, starting a week before their angioplasties and continuing for six months. After three months, 19 percent of those who took fish oil had restenosis, compared with 46 percent in the comparison group.
</TEXT>
