<HEAD>Onset Of Dry Weather Doesn't Concern Yellowstone Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Warmer, drier weather was returning today but officials expressed confidence that the fires that have blackened half of the oldest national park would not flare anew. Meanwhile, a newspaper report said park officials allowed fires to burn unattended for nearly three weeks after they were ordered to fight all fires because they wanted to protect pristine areas from the destruction caused by bulldozers, fire engines and irrigation equipment. In all, the fires have blackened roughly half the park's 2.2 million acres. Elsewhere, officials banned outdoor smoking in parts of northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and hundreds of firefighters prepared to go home after a 9,000-acre blaze in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> was contained. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> confirmed what firefighters in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> already knew: This summer was one of the park's warmest and driest on record. The weather service said Wednesday that temperatures at the Mammoth area of the park in June averaged 55.4, or 7.8 degrees higher than average. Average temperature in July was 66.4 degrees, 2.8 degrees above average. Temperatures were just slightly above normal in August. Rainfall totals were more than an inch less than normal each month, and the weather service said it is unlikely any major precipitation will offset the park's shortage soon. Steady rain Tuesday prevented the remaining blazes from growing significantly. Although skies have since cleared, longer nights are bringing longer periods of `` humidity recovery,'' when small fuels such as pine needles and twigs can soak up moisture, area commander <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Dittmer </PERSON> said. `` The worst is over,'' <PERSON> Dittmer </PERSON> said. Forecasts for the weekend called for another cooling trend, accompanied by a chance of showers, which could help the 4,500 firefighters battling the blazes. Winds are expected to remain calm. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported today that officials concerned about the destruction caused by firefighting equipment did not fight the Yellowstone portion of the Clover-Mist fire until nearly three weeks after <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>'s July 21 order that all fires be fought. Bulldozers were allowed in the park only on a case-by-case basis even at the height of the fires, the paper reported, and bulldozers were never used to make fire lines around the <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> part of the Clover-Mist blaze, which has burned 411,000 acres in the park and the adjacent Shoshone National Forest. The Times also reported that park rangers threatened a firefighting crew with citations for destroying park vegetation when they crossed a meadow with their truck to extinguish a spot fire. Elsewhere, state firefighters battling blazes that have charred more than 40,000 acres in northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> issued an emergency decree banning outdoor smoking in portions of 44 counties. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Partain </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION>, said `` the extreme danger'' posed by fire and acute dry conditions prompted the decree. Fire officials predicted they will have the <LOCATION> Vacaville </LOCATION> fire out by Saturday evening. The blaze has destroyed seven homes, blackened 27,000 acres and caused an estimated $ 1.83 million in damage. In <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, 400 firefighters were scheduled to go home from the Shady Beach fire in <ORGANIZATION> Willamette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> after the blaze was contained at just under 9,000 acres Wednesday night, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Tonn </PERSON> said. Another 400 firefighters are scheduled for release Friday, leaving fewer than 1,000 on the lines, he said.
