<HEAD>Slavic Students Demonstrate Against Albanians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of chanting, flag-waving <PERSON> Slavic </PERSON> students called a school strike today and marched around the capital of ethnically troubled <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, protesting alleged harassment by Albanians. About 1,000 teen-agers marched behind the red, blue and white flag of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s largest republic, <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, after going to four schools to declare a boycott of classes and collect supporters for their protest. Plainclothes police kept a close watch, but there was no atempt to interfere and uniformed police stopped traffic on the main thoroughfare to allow the marchers to pass. The march illustrated the high level of tension in this city of 200,000. `` We are afraid to go to school,'' said the students when youth officials tried to persuade them to return to class. On Tuesday night, about 5,000 Serbs and Montenegrins, both Slavs, rallied after a Serbian girl allegedly was attacked by an ethnic Albanian Monday night. That rally was one of the latest in a series of meetings backing <ORGANIZATION> Serbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, who wants more control over <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s two autonomous provinces of <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s poorest and most backward regions, has a history of ethnic tension between Serbs and Montenegrins, who see the province as their historic homeland, and the Albanians, who now make up about 90 percent of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s 2 million people. In 1981, ethnic riots left at least nine dead and prompted federal authorities in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> to impose martial law for a few weeks. <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s Albanians have not yet staged any public protests in response to the current wave of Slav rallies. But Serbs allege individual harassment by Albanians have increased and nervous residents in both ethnic groups report tension at a high level. Federal authorities dispatched extra police units, equipped with armored pesonnel carriers, to <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> earlier this month. Today's protest started when about 200 Slav teenagers walked up the central downtown street, chanting `` <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>,'' and `` We will give our lives, but we will not give <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>.'' Some participants said the march was sparked by the alleged rape attempt Monday night, but others said there had been fresh trouble Wednesday involving a fight between Albanian and Serbian students. A worried <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> mother, who did not identify herself, sobbed outside one school: `` Children should not solve problems. I have a child in there. I am afraid.'' A Serbian woman, looking at the march, said, `` What will happen now? Albanian kids know who is marching and they could do something.''
