<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A deranged man ran naked into <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s Cathedral, then killed an elderly usher and seriously injured a police officer with an iron prayerbook stand before being shot and killed by police, officials said The 250-pound attacker, identified as <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> DelGado </PERSON>, 32, of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, had attended morning Mass celebrated by Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> prior to Wednesday's attack and stood directly before the cardinal as he administered the Holy Eucharist, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> told reporters. `` I felt he was totally disoriented. The cathedral is a magnet for all people. People sleep in it and engage in the strangest behavior in the cathedral. I patted him on the shoulder and said, ` God bless you.' He stood for a moment and left,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> performed a purification rite before the 8 a.m. Mass today. The Rev. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON>, a spokesman, said the rite is performed `` whenever a sacred place has been violated and profaned.'' It was the first time the rite was performed in the 109-year history of the cathedral. `` While the cathedral has been desecrated, while this magnificent temple of almighty God, famous throughout the world, has been violated, we must not forget that two men were killed here last night,'' the cardinal told several hundred people who attended the morning service. `` It is for their souls I will be offering this Mass, as well as for the purification of the cathedral,'' the cardinal said. Wednesday evening, the man tore off all his clothes down the street from the historic midtown cathedral, walked one block to the church, chanting under his breath and carrying red carnations, according to witnesses. `` He suddenly stopped, stripped, and headed up the street. He was obviously disturbed,'' said a witness, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, 56. `` He was not aware of anybody else.'' Upon entering the church he repeatedly struck a woman praying in a pew, ripped the prayer book stanchion from the marble floor where it was bolted near the front altar, and then used it to strike and kill the 77-year-old usher, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Winters </PERSON>, and wound officer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McMann </PERSON>, police and witnesses said. `` Everyone backed away. Then the cops rushed in. -LRB- The woman -RRB- was screaming very loud that she was getting hit and needed help. But everyone was running away from her. We ran,'' said another witness, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. About six or seven people were present as the man began to attack the woman, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. `` He starts hitting her with his hand and he starts punching her.'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said that after the woman ran out of the church he told the police officer that `` ` a man is running around nude in the church, by the altar now and he's unarmed.' And the cop tries to convince him to leave.''' Meanwhile, the attacker `` picks up a metal stand and starts swinging it around, go wild crazy, and he hits the cop a couple of times,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. A backup police unit arrived and shot the attacker once in the chest, killing him, said Sgt. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>, a police spokesman. He fell to the floor in a center aisle, police said. The 3-foot-long metal stanchion was found about 7 feet away from him, said Detective <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON>. Winters, a <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> resident, died inside the front rail of the altar near the pulpit, police said. He suffered a large gash to the head, <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> said. <PERSON> McMann </PERSON>, 50, suffered a head injury that did not appear to be life-threatening, said Police Capt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>. He was in serious but stable condition early today at <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Marletta </PERSON>, a hospital administrator. The woman's identity and her injuries were not immediately known, police said. The cardinal said the man allegedly had committed acts of minor vandalism in and around the church in the past. `` Two people are dead and a police officer is seriously wounded,'' the cardinal said. `` There is no tragedy comparable to that. It's very serious to me and all Catholics.'' Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, who embraced <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> at the conclusion of a news conference outside the cathedral, said, `` We are very lucky he did n't assault the cardinal.''
