<HEAD>Bush Spending Record Amount On Television</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Bush aide confirming TV budget; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign will spend a modern record of about 60 percent of its $ 54 million budget for television advertising this fall, a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide said today. Presidential campaigns traditionally set aside about half of their federally restricted funds for paid media and the other half for campaign organization. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide, who spoke only on condition that he not be identified, said 60 percent or $ 32.4 million is `` a pretty accurate figure, which would make it the largest television expenditure in modern history.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, quoting an unnamed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide, said the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> campaign is benefiting so much from the use of money raised by the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for political activities that it can use a far larger share for advertising. Both campaigns are limited by federal law to a $ 54 budget, with $ 46 million coming from the federal treasury. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gearan </PERSON>, a spokesman for Democratic nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, said Wednesday, `` I think we'll be competitive with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign, but beyond that we do n't detail our spending.'' He said the high amount spent by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign is not surprising `` in this market.''
