<FIRST>r a PM-PullmanSuit     09-22 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pullman Suit,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Actions Nearing End In 23-Year-Old Racial Bias Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new court decision may finally end a 23-year-old racial discrimination case filed by black workers at an <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> railroad car manufacturing plant. The 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> issued a ruling Wednesday in the workers' case against <ORGANIZATION> Pullman-Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pullman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The court gave a partial victory to the workers, ordering a lower court to determine damages for workers who suffered discrimination between 1965 and 1974 but ruling in favor of the company in other aspects of the case. `` Few cases better represent the idea that the road to justice can be a long and tortured one,'' Circuit Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> wrote in a prologue to the decision. Complaints of racial discrimination were first brought by the workers shortly after President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> signed legislation that accommodated such claims. At the time, according to court documents, the factory in <LOCATION> Bessemer </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, was divided into 28 departments, some of them integrated but many either all-white or all-black. The black jobs paid less. In 1965, an arbitration decision opened up some jobs to blacks, but <PERSON> Pullman </PERSON> stopped its on-the-job training program that enabled many blacks to attain the skills needed to work at the plant. Four years later, <PERSON> Pullman </PERSON> entered into an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> to encourage blacks to move into the previously all-white departments and develop a program of outside vocational development. But several complaints of racial discrimination were filed with the <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> between 1966 and 1969. In 1972 the commission consolidated all the complaints and found that <PERSON> Pullman </PERSON> had discriminated in hiring, promotion and job assignments. Just before the commission's ruling, worker <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Swint </PERSON> filed a class-action lawsuit contending that <PERSON> Pullman </PERSON> practiced racial discrimination, and the case went to trial in 1974. <PERSON> Swint </PERSON> won, kicking off a litany of appeals, cross-appeals, trials and reversals. In the meantime, <PERSON> Pullman </PERSON> closed its <ORGANIZATION> Bessemer </ORGANIZATION> plant in 1982, putting some 3,500 people out of work. It was later purchased by <ORGANIZATION> Trinity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> and still makes railroad cars, employing about 600 people, said plant safety director <PERSON> Festus </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. Many of the original workers have since died, according to court documents. Four trials were held on <PERSON> Swint </PERSON>'s lawsuit, and the case made it to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1982. After the fourth trial, in 1986, both sides appealed once again to the 11th Circuit. Wednesday, the appeals court upheld a lower court's ruling that <PERSON> Pullman </PERSON>'s seniority system was not created or maintained in order to further discrimination. The appeals court also said evidence showed that discrimination in departmental assignments ended in February 1969. But one issue was reversed in the workers' favor and sent back to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, to determine damages. The appeals court said <PERSON> Pullman </PERSON> should be held liable for any discrimination occurring between October 1965 and January 1969 on job assignments. In addition, it said <PERSON> Pullman </PERSON> is liable for discrimination in promotions that happened between September 1966 and August 1974.
</TEXT>
