<HEAD>Minister Convicted In Beheading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A minister was convicted today of killing and beheading a church handyman and setting the church on fire in a bid to leave <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> and establish a new identity. The Circuit Court jury deliberated three hours Wednesday night and an hour this morning before finding <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> guilty of murder and arson. The sentencing portion of the trial was to begin later today. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>, 43, looked calm as the verdict was read. He was accused of killing handyman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheny </PERSON>, cutting off the man's head and other parts of his body to make identification difficult, and leaving the body in his <ORGANIZATION> Emmanuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oneness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pentecostal </ORGANIZATION>, which he then set on fire. Prosecutors said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> killed <PERSON> Matheny </PERSON>, 32, in June 1987 in an attempt to make it look as though he himself had been slain, so that he could adopt a new identity and start a new life. <PERSON> Matheny </PERSON>'s headless body was found in the ruins of the church, but the head was never found. The exact cause of death was never determined. In his closing argument, Assistant District Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON> called <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> a calculating killer `` with ice in his veins, not blood.'' `` You may never hear of a more cold-blooded, brutal murder than this one,'' <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON> said. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON> presented no witnesses on <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>'s behalf and did not make a closing statement, saying `` the real trial will begin'' if the jury is asked to impose the death sentence <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON> said he planned to argue that <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> was suffering from some sort of `` mental condition'' when <PERSON> Matheny </PERSON> was killed. <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> began planning the crime early last year, after receiving $ 50,700 from the sale of church property, unknown to other church officials, and after learning that he would not get a promotion he had expected. The prosecutor told the jury that <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> picked a name `` off a tombstone'' of a child who died in 1951 and began assembling identification papers in that person's name. The child had been born three days before <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> in 1944.
