 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> has accused <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada-Reno </ORGANIZATION> officials of persistent discrimination and said its refusal to allow a gay rodeo at a campus arena is just the latest example. `` Face it, if you're not a friend of the university and if you're in some minority group, you do n't have a chance there,'' state <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> Executive Director <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON> <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> said. Her office is working on six discrimination cases against the school _ involving complaints based on sex, age, race and handicap _ and has joined one lawsuit. Ms. <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> held a news conference Wednesday in front of the <ORGANIZATION> Lawlor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Events </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> to protest the school's refusal to allow the national gay rodeo championship finals to be held there Oct. 22-23, despite organizers' successful efforts to raise an extra $ 9,600 to cover expenses in advance. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Klasic </PERSON>, general counsel for the state university system, denied the school and <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> wrongfully reneged on a verbal deal in which officials agreed to hold the event if backers presented the $ 9,600. `` The dates are taken for the basketball team to practice,'' <PERSON> Klasic </PERSON> said. `` This agreement was reached on Aug. 31 after it appeared that the rodeo would n't be taking place.'' `` There's not a word of truth -LRB- to the discrimination charges -RRB-,'' he added. `` The coaches simply feel that the more time spent practicing in <LOCATION> Lawlor </LOCATION>, the better the home court advantage.'' Ms. <PERSON> Chase </PERSON>, however, said the basketball team normally defers to scheduled eve