<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixty-year-old sedans and newer Porsches, Maseratis and Corvettes will open their throttles along a 93-mile stretch of remote <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> highway this weekend in the nation's first legal open-road race in decades. But the first Silver State Classic has no prize money, no ticket sales and spectators are not encouraged, said race organizer and two-time <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> 500 winner <PERSON> Rodger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Vintage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Redondo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` This is not a spectator event,'' said <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, who won the 500 and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> championship in 1959 and 1962. `` This is a speed event all the way and is made so people with vintage cars can get them on the road and test them. `` No one will be allowed along the highways. Well, if people want they can watch the race start or wait at the finish line.'' `` There's really not much along the highway, mostly dirt roads, some driveways and farms,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. `` We'll have guards at all 32 highway access roads, though, so nobody gets it into their head to get in the way.'' That should n't be too difficult since the affected section of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> 318 through the mostly flat <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> crosses no other highways. Irrigation fields and distant ranch houses are the only signs of human life. The <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <O