<HEAD>Debate Coaches Unimpressed by Dukakis, Bush Debating Abilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Debate experts say that neither <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is any great shakes as a public speaker, and the winner of their first face-to-face showdown Sunday night may be whoever exceeds low expectations. Veteran forensic judges also agree that the candidates will try their utmost to observe the cardinal rule of presidential debates: avoid calamitous mistakes. That may be good politics, but it can make for dull debating, said members of the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> presidential debate judges panel. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Unger </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forensics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and chairman of the judges' panel, said these high-stakes debates `` are exercises in error-avoidance by the candidates.'' <PERSON> Unger </PERSON>, who also chaired <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> panels that judged the presidential debates in 1976, 1980 and 1984, said it is rare for a candidate to make a major gaffe like <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>'s in 1976 when he insisted that Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> was not dominated by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. All too often, he added, `` the candidates just sit there with their prepared answers desperately seeking out a question to which they can attach the answer.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Southworth </PERSON>, director of forensics and speech professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Redlands </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, said, `` I'm not convinced either one of them is going to be dynamic confronting each other. ... A lot will depend on how willing they are to take risks.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sferra </PERSON>, debate coach at <ORGANIZATION> J.K. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mullen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forensic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` Neither one is a terribly exciting speaker.'' `` I get the feeling they're too programmed to be debaters. You bring up an issue and they know where they're supposed to run and what to say,'' said <PERSON> Sferra </PERSON>. `` They're all so afraid they're going to say something wrong.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> engaged in 21 debates during the primaries with his rivals for the Democratic nomination, and he once moderated a public television debate series called `` The Advocates.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> faced off with his <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> rivals seven times. He also has a 1984 vice presidential debate with Democrat <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON> under his belt _ the one about which he boasted afterwards that he `` tried to kick a little ass.'' <PERSON> Melissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxey </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, director of forensics at <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said that in the primary debates, `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> demonstrated more range, positive and negative. He had very strong, persuasive responses when he was being attacked by -LRB- Al -RRB- <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> and -LRB- Jack -RRB- <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> in the early debates.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was `` real consistent. He does n't seem to make major goofs. He does n't have big highs or big lows,'' she said. <PERSON> Lanny </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Naegelin </PERSON>, a speech-theater arts specialist for the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said both <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> lack `` pizzazz'' as speakers, but `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is easier when he talks than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. It's more obvious when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> speaks that he's working at what he's doing.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>, national executive secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forensic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ripon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` has great debate skills, but he tends to be very monotone and flat in his presentation.'' He said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` is a very strained speaker. His voice tends to get a little screechy when he's excited.'' <PERSON> Sherry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, debate coach at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said that in collegiate debates, content wins more points than style. But in these presidential debates, `` the emphasis is much more on style,'' she said. `` That's what people remember. With -LRB- President -RRB- <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> four years ago, people remember how he looked, not what he said,'' she said. The seven-member panel will use a scorecard similar to that employed in collegiate and scholastic debates to determine a winner of the Sept. 25 Bush-Dukakis debate. It will also evaluate their second debate on Oct. 13 or 14, and their running mates' Oct. 5 encounter.
