<HEAD>Gandhi Withdraws Defamation Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, Indian (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> on Thursday withdrew a defamation bill that journalists and opposition politicians charged was an attempt at censorship. `` We praise all good deeds by the government,'' said <PERSON> Prithvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Chakravarthy </PERSON>, an editor of the Calcutta-based, Bengali-language newspaper <PERSON> Aajkal </PERSON> and member of the Editor's Guild of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. `` This withdrawal is one of the few good acts committed by the government in a long time, and we welcome it.'' In a statement, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said he was withdrawing the bill because `` it has aroused misapprehensions and misgivigs'' among the press and public. The law would have expanded the concept of defamation and abolished any presumption of innocence by journalists or others making disclosures construed as defamatory. It permitted up to two years' imprisonment for first offenders and up to five years' imprisonment for subsequent convictions. The government had said the legislation would protect people from irresponsible journalism. Newspapers denounced it as `` fascist'' and `` undemocratic'' and said it was an attempt to muzzle the press after a year of reports of alleged kickbacks involving defense contracts. Prominent Indians, including some of <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s friends, have been accused of receiving millions of dollars to facilitate contracts for <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> artillery guns and West German submarines. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> has denied receiving any money, and a government inquiry failed to note any wrongdoing. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said the issue of defamation still must be resolved. `` The freedom and rights of the individual are ... sacred. It is this that makes the issue of defamation serious,'' his statement said. The defamation bill was passed by the lower house of Parliament on Aug. 30, but it still required a vote by the upper house.
