<HEAD>Britain Orders Czechoslovak Diplomats Expelled For Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> accused three Czechoslovak diplomats Thursday of spying and ordered them to leave the country within two weeks. A Foreign Office announcement said the three envoys, including two military attaches, `` engaged in activities incompatible with their status'' _ diplomatic parlance for espionage. The diplomats are Maj. <PERSON> Bedrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramar </PERSON>, the assistant military and air attache; Maj. <PERSON> Vlastmil </PERSON> <PERSON> Netolicky </PERSON>, a member of the military attache's staff, and <PERSON> Paval </PERSON> <PERSON> Moudry </PERSON>, a member of the commercial section. The expulsions prompted speculation the envoys were linked with a London-based art dealer, <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Haarlem </PERSON>, who says he is Czechoslovakian and who is awaiting trial on charges of preparing to set up a spy ring. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> also has complained this year about supplies of Czechoslovak-made explosives reaching the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which is waging a bombing and shooting campaign to drive the British from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> refused to elaborate on its terse announcement. At the <ORGANIZATION> Czechoslovak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, a telephone receptionist told reporters after the 12:45 p.m. announcement that the embassy was closed for lunch and said later it was closed for the day. In <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Czechoslovak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rovensky </PERSON> said he had no comment. Czechoslovak Ambassador <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> was summoned to the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday morning and given the expulsion order. `` The Foreign Secretary -LRB- Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> -RRB- wishes it to be clearly understood that, while we wish to build up our relations with <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, we are not prepared to relax our policy on the sort of activities in which Maj. <PERSON> Kramar </PERSON>, Maj. <PERSON> Netolicky </PERSON> and Mr. <PERSON> Moudry </PERSON> have engaged,'' the statement said. <PERSON> Kramar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Moudry </PERSON> have been in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> since 1984, and <PERSON> Netolicky </PERSON> arrived in September 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said. They brought to seven the number of Czechoslovak diplomats <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has expelled since 1983, usually amid speculation the envoys were suspected of spying on behalf of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` There are certain instances, for example, where the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- the Soviet secret police -RRB- or the <ORGANIZATION> GRU </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Soviet military intelligence -RRB- has not wanted to get directly involved and has used Czech intelligence to do so,'' <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a defense analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Emmanuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, said in a radio interview Thursday. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Haarlem </PERSON>, who has a Dutch passport, was arrested last April at his <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> apartment. Police burst in and said they caught him using radio equipment to transmit signals `` to a foreign power.'' He has been indicted for trial at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Old </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bailey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. No date has been set. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> last expelled Soviet diplomats in September 1985. A total of 31 Soviets and 31 Britons, including businessmen and journalists, were ordered out of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in a series of retaliatory expulsions. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has expelled four other diplomats in the past month: a Tunisian who refused to pay hundreds of dollars of parking fines, a Vietnamese who brandished a gun at demonstrators, a Cuban who fired a gun in a street, and the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> ambassador.
