<HEAD>American School Children Perform Poorly In Science Education,
Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Science literacy among <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s school children is at an `` alarming and depressing'' level that may prevent many high school graduates from doing well in skilled jobs or college-level course, according to a study released Thursday. `` The Science Report Card,'' a federally funded project conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, found that more than half of the nation's 17-year-olds are so poorly educated in science that they can not benefit from special job training and can not perform work requiring basic technical understanding. Only seven percent of the 17-year-olds in the study demonstrated sufficient skills to do well in college-level science courses. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, called the findings `` depressing and alarming,'' and said the poor level of science education could be `` disastrous'' for the country. The science report card reflects data collected in 1986. It is the fifth national study of science skills among 9 -, 13 - and 17-year-olds to be conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> since Among the findings: _ Science achievement remains well below the results of the 1969 study for students at age 17, although there was a slight upturn observed in the 1982 and 1986 surveys _ Declines in science achievement are less for pupils aged 9 and 13, but the average achievement at age 13 remains below that measured in 1970, and achievement at age 9 has only now returned to the level measured in 1970 _ Science proficiency for black and hispanic students aged 13 and 17 remains at least four years behind the levels of white students of the same ages A marked difference in science proficiency is measured between girls and boys at the 13 and 17 age levels, although the genders measure approximately the same at age 9. At age 17, half of the males demonstrate an ability to analyze scientific procedures and data, while only a third of the females have such skills. In the study of physics, the study said, the gender gap is `` extremely large'' by the 11th grade. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the findings `` paint a stark picture of science education in our nation's schools.'' `` Scientific understanding is more and more a prerequisite for informed citizenship,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>. `` If <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s citizens of tomorrow are not scientifically literate, we place our very democracy at risk.'' She said that the lower level of science achievement by females and minority students is the most disturbing of the findings. `` By many measures of science proficiency, the inequalities for both minorities and females actually increase as students move through the grades,'' she said. <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, in a statement released by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, said the findings could be troubling for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future. `` When only a small number of our students can understand basic scientific concepts, the results are disastrous for the entire country,'' he said. `` Here we are, one of the great scientific giants of the world, and almost 60 percent of our successful 17-year-olds do n't have the scientific literacy required of informed citizens.'' The Science Report Card reinforces results of an international study released earlier this year that showed American school children at all levels performed far behind children of the same age in most of the other 14 nations surveyed. The Science Report Card study is financed by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> as part of a program called the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION>. National report cards also are issued in other subjects as part of the program.
