<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fourth anti-apartheid activist escaped detention and took refuge in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulate </ORGANIZATION>, where three other activists have been holed up for 10 days, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spokesman said today. Police issued an arrest warrant for <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON>, who fled Wednesday while being treated at <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> and went to the American consulate on the 11th floor of a downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> office tower. Authorities later said the warrant had been suspended. <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> claims he was assaulted by police the night he was detained. The consulate, which has been providing refuge to three other activists who escaped last week, decided to allow <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> to remain, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavis </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. All four detainees escaped guards while undergoing physiotherapy treatment at <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. Black activist <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> visited the consultate Wednesday and complained <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials would not let the detainees make direct contact with reporters. The 30-year-old <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON>, active in the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Soweto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, had been held five months, said attorneys at the <LOCATION> Cheadle </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> law firm that represents <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON>. An affidavit has been filed in which <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> alleges he was assaulted by police the night of his detention, the attorneys said. At the recommendation of a doctor, <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> was hospitalized four days after