<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WACO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> hit the campaign trail for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today with ridicule for `` born-again Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Pattons </PERSON>'' in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> who say they support a strong national defense. Without mentioning the name of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the president told a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> `` Texas Victory'88'' rally that liberal Democrats have had `` a deathbed conversion'' to <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> positions supporting the submarine-based Trident missile and the Stealth bomber. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was interrupted repeatedly by deafening screams and applause from about 9,000 <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students who hissed at the president's frequent mention of liberal Democrats. Signs on the wall read `` Rock ` Em Ron'' and `` Push For <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' `` When the liberals say ` family,' they mean ` big brother in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.' When we say ` family' we mean ` honor thy father and mother','' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. The crowd went wild. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> declared that under his and the vice president's leadership, `` our nation is again respected in the world, our armed forces are strong and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is at peace. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was stumping for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Beau </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulter </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, who is seeking the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, before joining the vice president at fund-raising dinner in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> tonight. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he recently vetoed a $ 299.5 billion defense authorization bill because he was convinced it would have harmed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military strength. He then invoked the name of Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Patton </PERSON>, a crusty and venerable World War II combat hero, in lambasting the Democratic ticket. `` But lately, some liberal leaders have seen what was happening to them in the polls and had a deathbed conversion,'' he said. `` They'd have you believe that they're born-again Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Pattons </PERSON>. But if we go the way they want to go, our defenses will run out of gas in no time.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has charged repeatedly that his Democratic rival, the governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, was soft on defense issues and would weaken the national security. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has said he opposes the rail-based MX missile and has voiced concerns about how far the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should go in deploying B-1 bombers. But in an effort to deflect the vice president's criticism, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> donned a military helmet and took a ride in an M-1 battle tank last week at a defense contractor's plant in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> to underscore his argument that he believes in a strong military. The president said that when <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> liberals talk of supporting new weapons systems, `` they whisper that they're also for delaying deployment of both systems -LRB- the Trident and the Stealth bomber -RRB- pending the outcome of arms talks, which could drag on for years, while the Soviets could be deploying new systems of their own.'' Said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>: `` They shout loudly that the're for maintaining the effectiveness of the land-based leg of our strategic -LRB- missile -RRB- triad. But they're against the modern missile systems that will be available for years to come and would like to see an end to the flight testing needed to develop new systems.'' On Wednesday, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> offered <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> some advice on the vice president's first nationally televised debate with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on Sunday in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. The president told reporters he advised <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to `` take no prisoners'' in the face-off at <ORGANIZATION> Wake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. During today's trip, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also planned to visit the Johnson Space Center in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, where he was to meet with the five Discovery space shuttle astronauts who are preparing for a Sept. 29 launch. His joint appearance with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is their second since the vice president won the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential nomination in mid-August. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, with its 29 electoral votes and status as <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s home state, is a pivotal campaign battleground for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. After <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> tapped <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as his running mate, the senator was allowed to remain on the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> ballot in his bid for a fourth <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> term under the so-called `` Lyndon Law,'' which was passed to allow <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> to run simultaneously for re-election to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and for the vice presidency with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> in 1960. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s last visit to the space center was a grim one, coming only days after the disastrous explosion of the Challenger space shuttle on Jan. 28, 1986. The Challenger's seven crew members perished when their spacecraft erupted in a giant fireball