<HEAD>Police Continue Crackdown But Withdraw Warrant For Fourth Escaped
Detainee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police continued a nationwide crackdown on government opponents Thursday, but they backtracked on a detainee who escaped and joined three other activists holed up at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Consulate. Police issued, then withdrew an arrest warrant for <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON>, who escaped Wednesday while being treated at a hospital and fled to the 11th-floor consulate in a downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> office building. Consular officials, who have provided refuge for three prominent activists since their escape Sept. 13, allowed <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> to remain while his case is assessed, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavis </PERSON> said. Police have pledged not to arrest the three initial escapees if they leave the consulate, but Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said a multipronged crackdown against other activists is under way. Across the country this week, more than two dozen activists have been detained or barred from political activities, offices of anti-apartheid groups have been raided, and pedestrians and motorists in urban centers have been subjected to random searches. The crackdown comes during an increase in bombings, including five in a nine-hour span late Wednesday and early Thursday. Authorities said 38 people were injured, including 18 whites at a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> bus terminal and 19 blacks eight hours later at a disco on the other side of the city. The owner of the disco said three white men entered, then left without drinking any of the beers they had ordered, shortly before the explosion. Police blame most recent bombings on the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the major guerrilla group fighting white-minority rule. But activists believe right-wing vigilantes or a covert security force unit carried out the recent bombing of a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> building used by anti-apartheid groups. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said the security crackdown was intended to counter an alleged campaign to disrupt nationwide municipal elections next month. Activists advocate a boycott of the elections and say the segregated black council seats at stake are components of a white-controlled system that excludes blacks from central government. Police also have been targeting activists expected to participate in a national anti-apartheid conference this weekend in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. The main sponsor of the conference, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions, said Thursday that eight of its members were detained and four barred from leaving the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> area. <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON>, 30, was active in the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Soweto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and had been held since April 23, his attorneys said. <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> alleged that he was assaulted by police on the night of his detention, and he was hospitalized four days after he was detained, the attorneys said. Police issued an arrest warrant for <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> on Thursday and said he was wanted for illegal weapons possession and intimidation, but several hours later the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the warrant was suspended. The department said the case against <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> dealt only with weapons possession, not with any other alleged offense, and was referred to the attorney general for consideration. Authorities did not elaborate on what would happen to <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> if he left his refuge. The government has said it will act against the three activists who escaped to the consulate last week. They are <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Morobe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Valli </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosa </PERSON>, leaders of the banned <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest anti-apartheid coalition, and <PERSON> Vusi </PERSON> <PERSON> Khanyile </PERSON>, chairman of the banned <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crisis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The three eluded guards while receiving physiotherapy at <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, the same facility that <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> escaped from. The three have called for the release of all political detainees and have refused to leave the consulate despite the government assurances. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say the activists will not be expelled from the consulate despite a worldwide policy of not granting asylum in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic missions. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
