few in number,'' he said. Mrs. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, who described herself as a lifelong political activist most concerned with persuading qualified people to run for office, said <PERSON> McCrery </PERSON> cast a couple of votes `` that put up little red flags'' _ including opposition to a 60-day notification for plant closings and a catastrophic health care bill. `` I felt like he has cast a straight party line vote even when it hurt his district and it would not have hurt his standing in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for him to have voted differently,'' she said. The incumbent said he voted against the plant closing provision because it could have pushed small businesses into bankruptcy and would have discouraged expansion. He said the health care bill `` was not in the best interest of the district.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said she decided to enter the race because no strong candidate was emerging to challenge <PERSON> McCrery </PERSON>. `` I walked down the levee and through the cotton fields and decided I would run.'' It certainly was n't the governor's idea, she said. `` When I called him up on that Saturday morning and told him I planned to run for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and asked him if that would cause him any problems, there was dead silence,'' she said. `` When he came back on, he said ` Mom, are you serious?''' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Patti </PERSON>, recently appeared at a $ 1,000 per couple fund-raiser for his mother. Last spring, the governor drew the ire of state Democrats when he supported <PERSON> McCrery </PERSON>. <PERSON> McCrery </PERSON>, whose campaign raised about $ 80,000 with a fundraiser featuring retired Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, a major figure in the Iran-Contra controversy, said he has done in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> exactly what he promised to do. `` No. 1 is what is in