<HEAD>Moscow Opera Conductor Tells Reasons for Defecting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A conductor of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Bolshoi Opera said Thursday he defected to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> because his outspoken doubts about Soviet politics made him a second-class citizen and hampered his work in his own country. `` While we were trying to build one type of society in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, we were in fact building one very different, one in which it was very difficult to live and in which there was little hope for the future,'' said <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON>, who sought asylum at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> last week while visiting that nation. `` I am an outspoken person,'' <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON> told a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> news conference. `` I could not disguise my feelings,'' <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON> said, and he believes that `` informers reported back to the authorities.'' <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON> said he first experienced trouble on his return to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1976 after a stay of nearly six years in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, where he was the principal conductor of the National Symphonic Orchestra in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paz </LOCATION>. Although he was never charged or openly accused of disloyalty to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, he was unable to find a permanent post for four years after his return. The situation improved slightly after he wrote a letter to <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who was then the Soviet president, and from 1980 until his defection <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON> was one of several conductors at the <LOCATION> Bolshoi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, conducting more that 500 performances. <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON> met last week with <PERSON> Mstislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON>, another Soviet defector, who is now director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The two were acquainted years ago in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, when <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON> was principal conductor of the Armenian State Symphony in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON> was unfamiliar with <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON>'s work and had no comment on the defection, said a spokeswoman for <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON>. `` They had been very much out of touch and Mr. <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON> did not know that Mr. <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON> was conducting at the Bolshoi. He did, however, recognize his face,'' said the spokeswoman, <PERSON> Nadya </PERSON> <PERSON> Efremov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON>, whose defection was disclosed Wednesday, has not received any invitations to work in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but told reporters: `` I am an optimist.'' The Soviet conductor said that he had great respect for <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his attempts to reform Soviet society. Although there have been improvements in literature, film and theater, `` in music, things are the opposite,'' said <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON>. `` The political leadership is not as interested in music as they are in literature and film,'' he said. The world of Soviet music is run by `` the same people in the ministries and the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> who have sat there for the past 20 years. It is impossible for them to change,'' he said. The Bolshoi Theater, which includes an opera and a ballet company, remains a political fiefdom where the level of artistic discussion `` can be compared to any graveyard in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>,'' and the director fires those who disagree with him, he said. `` I do not consider myself a traitor or a defector,'' he said. But `` I felt I was under suspicion and did not have the confidence of the people who ran the musical world. They did not have confidence in my political views.'' Because of that, he said, he was considered `` a second class citizen'' and `` a member of the lowest category'' of society. <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON> said that his only close relative in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was a sister. His wife died two years ago, they had no children, and his parents are deceased, he said.
