<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone-Hamilton Stores, Bjt,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fires Leave Yellowstone Concessionaire Stocked with Tourist Items</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST YELLOWSTONE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Povah </PERSON> is up to his warehouse ceiling in sweatshirts, coffee mugs, fishing tackle and thousands of other items normally carted home by tourists during a typical Yellowstone summer. But the summer of'88 was far from typical in the country's first national park Forest fires that raged over half of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>'s 2.2 million acres meant evacuation and early closure of many facilities It also meant the hasty exit of thousands of visitors who ordinarily would crowd the aisles of <PERSON> Povah </PERSON>'s 15 retail stores past Labor Day. `` Will I have to re-order inventory for next year? God, I hope not!'' said <PERSON> Povah </PERSON>, 43, president of his family's <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the oldest concessioner under the jurisdiction of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` First we had the Great Depression, then World War II, then the'59 earthquake, then the Arab oil embargo, then the'76 Teton Dam disaster, and now the fires. There are always hurdles in the road. This is just another one. I try to be philosophical. `` Wan na buy a T-shirt cheap?'' <PERSON> Povah </PERSON>'s quip is typical of the kind of humor he says has helped his family cope with <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Nature </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> bureaucrats during the nearly three quarters of a century <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> has been in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>. `` We basically fly with one eye open anyway,'' said <PERSON> Povah </PERSON>. `` Who's to say in August of'88 that we wo n't have a gas shortage in July of'89 and the tourists wo n't come anyway? The company philosophy is conservative. That means we have a 72-year history of annual crapshoots.'' <PERSON> Povah </PERSON>'s grandfather, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashworth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, arrived in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> by train in 1905 from <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, and went to work for the <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which then ran the commissary. Through three generations of its owners' grit, hunches, neck protrusion and luck, <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, which formally began in 1915 when its founder bought out a retiring storekeeper at Old Faithful, has grown into a multimillion-dollar operation. Today Hamilton Stores concessions are scattered throughout the park. They include service stations, snack bars, grocery and general merchandise stores, and camera shops. They also provide 12 dormitories for their 800 summer employees. <PERSON> Povah </PERSON> says his family will remember this year for a long time. `` It was wild,'' he said, shaking his head. `` In May and June we were doing a tremendous business, so in July we heavily re-ordered. Then the fires came. `` We did n't lose any facilities but we had smoke-damaged merchandise and a helluva lot of inconvenience.'' He even spent a few days helping fight fires with his company's two fire trucks `` There'd be a power outage and we'd be running around trying to save ice cream. Then Old Faithful was threatened and we were shuffling all the merchandise around,'' <PERSON> Povah </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Povah </PERSON> recalled the night he and his three children, headed home to West Yellowstone from the park, got cut off and had to wait it out while hundreds of firefighters fought one of the biggest blazes. `` The kids were saying ` Uh, Dad, I think you should turn around' and I looked to see flames everywhere,'' said <PERSON> Povah </PERSON> `` I tried to say ` No problem' but I was a little worried.'' So how's Povah going to relax after such a stressful summer? `` I'm going to take a bus from <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> over 18,000-foot-high mountain passes,'' he said. `` That should prepare me for next summer in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>.''
