<HEAD>Baltimore Mayor Says Legalize Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Decriminalizing heroin and crack would remove the profit from the drug trade, reduce street crime, and ease the burden on the legal system, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> said Thursday. `` I'd like to see leading the war on drugs, the surgeon general, not the attorney general,'' <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> said at a debate sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and held before 100 business executives, students, and journalists. <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON>, whose support of decriminalization caused a stir at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> in April, plans to testify Sept. 29 at a congressional hearing on the issue. `` I was a prosecutor for 7 -LCB- years and I know what I'm talking about,'' <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> said. `` As long as we continue doing what we're doing, children are going to be lured into the drug trade and dirty needles are going to kill people I want to treat people with the disease called addiction as patients, not as criminals. `` You have to reallocate those resources to the public health system, toward education, treatment and prevention,'' he added. He also called for a national commission that would examine prescription and illegal drugs, alcohol and cigarettes to determine the most effective way to regulate each. <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> shared the dais with <PERSON> Georgette </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a decriminalization advocate whose 1987 book `` Crimewarps'' about future crime trends was nominated for a Pulitzer Prize. Opposing them were <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON>, a special agent with the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Director </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Substance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, who founded the <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> drug rehabilitation program. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> showed the audience a bottle of multicolored pills, a container of liquid methadone and a bottle of brandy as examples of substances that are widely abused even though they are legal. <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON> disagreed with <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON>'s assertion that Prohibition was a failure. <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON> noted a decline in alcoholism and cirrhosis of the liver during the Prohibition years, while <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> said making alcohol illegal gave rise to organized crime and deprived the government of tax revenue.
