<HEAD>Uneasy Calm Prevails in Riot-Torn Louisiana Community</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Decades of racism and black unemployment made it inevitable that <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION> would see an outbreak of violence like this week's rock-throwing and arson following the killing of a black man, a civil rights leader says. `` <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>'s been dodging the bullet for 25 years,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> English </PERSON> of the local <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> chapter. The violence Tuesday and Wednesday nights, set off when a white woman shot a black man, was confined to a few blocks in <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION>, a mostly residential neighborhood of modest houses and small businesses about six miles from downtown. Police spokeswoman <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chadwick </PERSON> said no problems were reported in <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> after dozens of heavily armed Special Response Team officers left the area early Thursday. Police took down roadblocks that sealed off the area for about four hours Wednesday night, but <PERSON> Chadwick </PERSON> said beefed up patrols were ready to seal off the area again if violence resumed. The rioting was set off by the killing Tuesday night of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, 22. A 17-year-old white girl was arrested and officials said the shooting followed a drug deal that went bad, with the victim an innocent bystander. Black leaders said another factor was anger over the killing of a black teen-ager by a white teen-ager at a restaurant last month. And, they said, there was lingering frustration over the recent acquittal in west <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> of three law officers accused in the beating death of a <LOCATION> Florien </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, black man arrested last Christmas Day on suspicion of drunk driving. But those three incidents were only catalysts, black leaders said. The Rev. <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> and a long-time <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION> civil rights leader, blamed long-standing `` institutional racism'' for the trouble. But he warned blacks against violence. `` Destruction is not the way. We need reasoning and logic,'' said <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. The Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> blamed the unrest on poverty and illiteracy. `` They've had too much access to guns and drugs and too little access to jobs, to scholarships,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>. `` In that city today, we must make the appeal for the haves and the have nots, the black and the white to come together and study war no more,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. Classes at Caddo Parish schools near the riot area continued without interruption, although Assistant Superintendent <PERSON> Ealie </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> said absences would be excused if parents decided to keep their children home. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said security would be beefed up at this weekend's high school football games, where there have been occasional race-related problems over the years. But board official <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said the security was planned before the <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> incident because of a rash of minor stadium crimes. Tuesday's violence centered around a small grocery where the white shooting suspect and her companion fled after <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> was shot. The grocery and a neighboring liquor store were gutted by fire and a television news team's car was burned while hundreds of people rampaged, breaking store windows and looting. Five arrests were reported in connection with the rioting and <PERSON> Tamala </PERSON> <PERSON> Vergo </PERSON>, 17, was booked with second-degree murder. Official police reports contain few details but individual officers, city officials and one witness indicated <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> was an innocent bystander felled after a drug deal went sour. Wednesday night's violence was on a much smaller, less intense scale. There were reports of sporadic gunfire and at least one fire. But no injuries or arrests were reported as police let the troublemakers disperse by themselves. Residents say <PERSON> Cedar </PERSON> <PERSON> Grove </PERSON> once was a quiet, racially mixed suburb that has deteriorated for a variety of reasons. The area is now predominantly black, the apparent result of `` white flight'' during the civil rights years. One police officer called the small area where most of the violence occurred a `` curb-service crack store.'' <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamness </PERSON>, a former resident who moved away five years ago, said people of both races have left because of crime, particularly the drug trade. `` At one time it was peaceful,'' said <PERSON> Chamness </PERSON>. `` When I was young, children could walk up and down the streets without fear. Our moms could walk to the store. I do n't know what happened to the neighborhood.''
