<HEAD>Bush Will Spend $32 Million on Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan to spend a record amount on TV advertising continues a trend toward presidential campaign budgets dominated by paid media expenditures, political analysts said Thursday. Four years ago, Democratic nominee <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> spent more than $ 20 million on media and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> spent about $ 25 million. This fall, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> expects to mount a $ 32 million-plus TV blitz. That's at least 60 percent of the combined $ 54 million that the candidate and his national party can spend directly. A <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said 60 percent, or $ 32.4 million, is `` a pretty accurate figure, which would make it the largest television expenditure in modern history.'' <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gearan </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic nominee, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would be competitive on the airwaves but declined to be specific. Both candidates are relying on their parties to raise tens of millions of dollars in unrestricted `` soft money'' for political activities at the state and national levels, enabling them to divert a greater percentage of their own limited campaign resources to media. The soft money is available for party-building activities including lawn signs, phone banks, generic TV ads, voter registration and get-out-the-vote drives. Such expenditures do not count toward the candidates' overall spending ceiling. <PERSON> Bay </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s campaign treasurer in both 1980 and 1984, said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> campaign forked over several million dollars for get-out-the-vote activities four years ago. `` If you can get the party to raise it ... that's $ 3 million to $ 4 million dollars you'd obviously put to media time,'' she said. `` It's a very effective way to be running an organization. Usually the states know better how to raise and spend the money.'' The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> game plan represents the increasingly critical role played by TV advertising. `` The very first thing I did -LRB- in 1984 -RRB- was take 50 percent of the total amount we were allocated and put it to media,'' said <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON>. `` Then if any money could be picked up -LRB- from other areas -RRB-, we moved that money to media. That's where any loose money went because we felt it was the most effective way to reach voters.'' Democrats and Republicans alike say they are not surprised by this year's heavy tilt toward media spending, given the increasing importance of TV ads and the high cost of buying air time, particularly during widely watched events such as the Olympics and the World Series. But they caution against treating it as a revolutionary development. `` It's not a dramatic escalation of media dollars,'' said Republican consultant <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON>. `` It should n't be overstated. It's just incrementally more than has been spent before, in real terms and in percentage of the overall budget.''
