<HEAD>Cardinal Prays for Slain Cathedral Usher, Deranged Attacker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Violence in <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s Cathedral that left an usher and his deranged attacker dead was a `` special sacrilege and tragedy,'' Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said Thursday as he resanctified the church and prayed for the assailant and victim alike. It was the first time in the 109-year history of the church that the rite to purify a profaned sacred place was performed. The attack occurred about 8 p.m. Wednesday, an hour before the church would close, when a man ran naked through the cathedral and bludgeoned part-time usher <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Winters </PERSON>, 77, to death with an iron stanchion. He also injured a worshiper and a police officer before being shot to death by police. The cardinal had seen the man, <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> DelGado </PERSON>, 32, at morning Mass that day when <PERSON> Delgado </PERSON> joined the line for communion. `` It was clear instantly there was something seriously wrong,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. `` I looked up and there he is, standing before me, a very big man, a very powerful looking man, bizarrely dressed.'' `` He rolled his eyes. He opened and closed his eyes. He rolled his head and the priest who was standing next to me whispered, ` Be careful. He gets violent,''' the cardinal said. <PERSON> DelGado </PERSON>, a vagrant who was born on St. Patrick's Day in 1956 had pleaded guilty 11 times since 1982 to charges including assault, attempted robbery and burglary. He had been in the cathedral many times and had committed minor acts of vandalism there before. Many homeless people enter the church to avoid the heat or cold or to find a place to sleep. Despite the attack, the archdiocese will not change its open-door policy, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. `` I would hate to see us now get defensive.'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> was not in the cathedral when <PERSON> DelGado </PERSON>, naked and carrying red carnations and his