<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THIEF RIVER FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's not as cheap as a string around the finger, but a new gadget for the forgetful gives a gentle nudge at the waistline as a reminder of whatever it is the wearer wants to be reminded. A psychologist invented the vibrating gadget named the MotivAider. The invention is based on what psychologist <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Levinson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Thief </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> says is obvious _ that the human brain does a poor job of making sure its owner does all the things that a person has firmly resolved to do. The gadget he calls an `` intention arousing device,'' is about 2 inches square and hangs like a beeper from the user's belt. Set for intervals of one minute to 24 hours, it flutters silently against the waistline. The wearer has programmed in his or her memory what the reminder means, says <PERSON> Levinson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ros </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairbank </PERSON>, who lost to <PERSON> Martina </PERSON> <PERSON> Navratilova </PERSON> in the Wimbledon quarterfinals this year, told the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> that it helped improve her backhand. Her problem was failing to get her racquet back early enough and to `` hit over the ball,'' she said in a phone interview. She set the MotivAider at three-minute intervals and wore it during practice. When it vibrated, she said to herself `` Early preparation!'' and that's what she focused on. `` I would n't say it made me win a match,'' she said, `` but it developed my backhand and my confidence in my backhand.'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Priedeman </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Deephaven </ORGANIZATION> sales manager, says he improved his golf game. When the $ 79.95 battery-operated device fluttered at three-minute intervals he told himself: `` Keep your head down, slow on the backswing and stop before you come down again.'' The result: `` I shot 10 strokes less than I ever had before.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The battle over which <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> holds title to the original <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> stew moves on as a losing team from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> heads for <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> in November for a rematch. <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodside </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick-Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Isles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> residents were n't surprised they came up on the short end of last week's contest, held in <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` How could we win on their turf?'' he said. The Virginians will defend their title during <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION>'s Main Street Jubilee on Nov. 19. <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Taunton </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> cooking team, said when <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, announced plans to hold a stew cook-off during its Heritage Festival, `` we felt we had to be there to defend our honor.'' The debate over which of the two communities can rightfully claim the original <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> stew recipe began when the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> town challenged other Brunswicks in the nation to a cook-off, said <ORGANIZATION> Woodside </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> county accepted the challenge, but was unable to attend last year's cook-off in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, he said. `` They even went so far as to approach their <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION> to get a resolution claiming they had the original <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stew </ORGANIZATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Woodside </ORGANIZATION> said. So, in the spirit of competition, the <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> legislative delegation approached the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and received a similar resolution. Chef <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s version of <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> stew uses a chicken base instead of the pork or beef used by the Georgians and is not as spicy as the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> version.
