<FIRST>u w AM-FAA-WindShear     09-22 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FAA-Wind Shear,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlines Told To Equip Aircraft With Devices To Detect Wind Shear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday ordered airlines to equip all their aircraft with devices that will help pilots detect and escape from deadly wind shears. Powerful shears called microbursts have been called the No. 1 killer of airline passengers and have been responsible for at least five fatal airline crashes and 500 deaths in the last decade, according to aviation safety experts. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> regulation was announced by the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which said the devices, to be phased into operation in all aircraft of 30 or more seats over the next four years, will cost $ 40,000 to $ 50,000 per airplane. About 3,600 commercial jet transport planes also will be required to have the devices, department officials said. A microburst is a powerful downburst of air caused by a sudden change in wind direction. Such a downburst struck a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> L-1011 as it was attempting to land at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> in 1985 and literally forced the plane into the ground, killing 134 people. The accident focused increased attention on developing and installing sophisticated ground radar that would provide advanced warning of shears along departure and approach lanes, but the radar is not expected to be available until the early 1990s. At the same time, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and industry began taking a closer look at devices for the cockpit that would provide pilots with a clear indication when their plane is facing wind shear conditions. <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> two years ago began installing the equipment being required by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and today has the devices in 112 of its 191 aircraft, according to <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. It could not immediately be determined whether other airlines have bought similar equipment. Under the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> regulation the airlines will be allowed to phase in installation of the equipment over about four years. Half of an airline's fleet must have the devices within 27 months, three-fourths of the fleet within 39 months and the rest of the fleet within 51 months. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said the equipment `` will enhance safety by giving pilots a valuable tool for coping with the dangerous wind shear phenomenon.'' `` Experience has shown that pilots can recover successfully from wind shear encounters if they can recognize the situation quickly enough and have sufficient information to execute escape maneuvers,'' <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. But the aviation industry has been divided on the value of the cockpit devices. Some experts note that the equipment is not a radar that would give advance warning of a shear. Instead, the system consists of sensitive equipment that calculates airspeed and other factors and tells a pilot when the plane is in the midst of wind shear conditions. Critics of the equipment have suggested that by then it may already be too late to fly through a microburst, especially if the plane is close to the ground, as in a takeoff or landing. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> rule also requires airlines to provide pilots with increased training on wind shear recognition and recovery procedures while using the new equipment. Pilots are divided as to how best to fly through a shear. Many insist that a powerful microburst such as the one that struck the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> plane in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> or the one encountered by a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jetliner that crashed as it was taking off from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> in 1982 is virtually impossible to escape. The Pan Am crash left 154 people dead. The airlines as well as the pilots union have urged speedy development and installation of so-called Doppler radar at major airports so that shears can be detected in advance and pilots can maneuver around them or not depart. The first of 17 such Doppler radars are scheduled to be installed at airports between 1990 and 1992. About 30 additional radars would be installed at other airports later under an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> contract scheduled to be awarded later this year. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> also have under way a five-year research program aimed at eventually developing a more advanced wind shear detection device for the cockpit that would be able to warn a pilot in advance when it is about to encounter shear conditions.
</TEXT>
