<HEAD>House Panel Approves Sanctions Over Use Of Poison Gas Against
Kurds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Brushing aside <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration objections, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved on Thursday legislation imposing sanctions on <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for its alleged use of poison gas `` against Kurdish insurgents and unarmed Kurdish civilians.'' The committee acted after senior Republican members told administration officials that there is strong bipartisan support for the measure in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and urged them to reconsider their opposition. One official, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Burley </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> Affairs, told the panel the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration believes the sanctions legislation is ` ` premature'' and `` counterproductive'' because it is likely to undercut intense diplomatic efforts aimed at preventing the future use of chemical weapons by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> `` I am very disappointed in the statement that you read,'' said Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Broomfield </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Mich </LOCATION>., the panel's senior <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> member `` A lot of effort has gone into making this a bipartisan effort. I think this is a very measured response and I think the administration will see when it hits the floor the large bipartisan support it will have.'' Unlike sanctions legislation approved earlier by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> resolution does not accuse <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> of waging a war of genocide against the country's Kurdish minority. And the sanctions it would impose, at least initially, are generally less severe. The resolution declares that the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> army has destroyed Kurdish villages in northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and adds: `` Substantial evidence exists that the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> army has been using chemical weapons against Kurdish insurgents and unarmed Kurdish civilians.'' It calls that `` a gross violation of international law.'' In a series of initial steps, the resolution would prohibit government-to-government or commercial arms sales to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> as well as sensitive high technology items. It authorizes the president, after consultation with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, to take a series of other punitive actions against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> including barring Iraqi exports, including petroleum products, from entering the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, barring or restricting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, denying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> financial credits or financial guarantees and opposing loans to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> by international financial institutions. The resolution authorizes the president to waive any or all of the sanctions if he certifies to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is not using chemical weapons in violation of international law, that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has provided `` reliable assurances'' that it will not use chemical weapons in the future and that it is willing to permit on-site inspection by impartial observers. The committee approved the measure on a voice vote after acting to include a prohibition against the export to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> of any chemical that might be used to produce chemical weapons and to authorize the president to bar the sale of an entire steel plant in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee's action follows the issuance on Wednesday of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> staff report based on interviews with more than 200 of the 65,000 Kurdish refugees who fled into <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> following the alleged poison gas attacks on their villages by <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> aircraft. The report concludes that `` overwhelming evidence exists'' that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used chemical weapons against the Kurds and that hundreds, perhaps thousands, of people likely were killed. The only committee member to oppose the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> resolution was Rep. <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, R-Wis., who said that while the use of poison gas is `` despicable,'' sanctions against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> will only hurt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exporters But Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilbray </PERSON>, D-Nev., said that to do nothing is unacceptable `` If we do n't do something we are going to have tell our own children and grandchildren that we sat by while an entire people was exterminated,'' he said. <PERSON> Burley </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is encouraged by a recent statement by the foreign minister of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> which he said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats interpret as meaning that `` there will be no future use of chemical weapons.'' Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON>, D-Calif., told <PERSON> Burley </PERSON>: `` I am intrigued by your logic which looks at a criminal act, sweeps it aside and takes the word of a criminal that he will not take criminal actions in the future. <PERSON> Burley </PERSON> replied: `` We believe enacting these sanctions now will lessen our influence ... We do not believe that sanctions now would bring us closer to the objective we both share, ending the use of chemical weapons by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>.''
