<HEAD>President Relishes Return To Space</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf, Two days, to correct to three days; SUBS 6th
graf, In a speech, to update with speech delivered; SUBS 8th graf,
Reagan's itinerary, with seven grafs to update and add color; SUBS
12th graf, The flight, to correct months to 32; also fixes category
code in header</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven days before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hopes to return to manned space flight, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lauded the `` seven heroes'' of the Challenger on Thursday and pledged, `` You can delay our long trek to greatness, but you can not halt it.'' Returning to the scene of one of his most emotional times as president, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told workers at the Johnson Space Center: `` Soon the world will be watching as five brave Americans lift off from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is going to space again _ and we are going there to stay.'' Three days after the Challenger blew apart on Jan. 28, 1986, little more than a minute after liftoff, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> went to the Johnson Space Center to console the relatives and friends of the seven crew members who died. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s worst space tragedy shook the nation and threw the space program into disarray. In a speech to <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> employees a week before Discovery's blast-off, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` Our early settlers knew great risks and made great sacrifices, but with their sacrifices, they moved the frontier forward and built a great nation. `` Neither can we stand still, nor be content, and we are not afraid,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` Ill fortune can slow us down, but it can not stop us.'' Upon his arrival in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was asked if he wanted to go up in space. `` I've been there for several years,'' the president chuckled as he climbed into his limousine. At the sprawling space center, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> greeted the five Discovery crewmen: commander <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauck </PERSON>, co-pilot <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Covey </PERSON> and mission specialists <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lounge </PERSON>, <PERSON> George </PERSON> `` Pinky'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilmers </PERSON>. The president was treated to a brief tour of a mockup of a space shuttle. The crew, clad in royal blue jumpsuits, led <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> up the stairs to peer through an open hatch in the two-story-high mockup of the shuttle. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, queried after his brief tour whether he wished he committed more money to the space program, replied, `` I've tried to do all that's possible. We've had some problems,'' he added, apparently referring to the Challenger tragedy. `` This program is the highest priority,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. The president then walked toward the end of the mock shuttle, where he addressed 8,000 to 10,000 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> employees, contractors and their families, many of whom waved tiny <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags under the bright <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> sun and roared their approval during <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s speech. At the end of his speech, <PERSON> Hauck </PERSON> presented <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> with a royal blue jacket and told him that the insignia patch from the Discovery mission would be flown into space with the shuttle crew and returned and presented to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the end of the mission. Before meeting the astronauts, who are under a modified quarantine before their scheduled launch, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> underwent a medical examination in which he was pronounced free of any disease that could be easily transmitted. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s senior aides and <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> detail were required to complete medical data forms before they were cleared to enter the space center with the president. Only <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was to have direct contact with the astronauts. Next Thursday, the shuttle is scheduled to blast off from <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, on a four-day stay in orbit _ a mission that will include the launching of a $ 100 million communications satellite. The flight will be the first in 32 months _ a wrenching period in which <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> underwent a series of management and other changes, including a redesign of the shuttle boosters, emanating from a presidential commission's findings resulting from the accident. The tragedy was a monumental setback to the space program, which was the first to put a man on the moon and which had led the world in exploration after initially playing catchup with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the late 1960s. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s space-center stop came on a day in which the president was making campaign appearances in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> for Republican presidential candidate <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Beau </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulter </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, who is trying to wrest Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s seat from him. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is running for both the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the vice presidency under a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law that permits such a dual candidacy. The president was wrapping up his campaign day by sharing the stage with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at a $ 1,000-a-plate fund-raising dinner for some 2,500 Republicans. In the Johnson Space Center pep talk, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that `` when we launch the space shuttle Discovery, even more than the thrust of Discovery's great engines, it will be the inspiring courage of our heroes, and the hopes and dreams of every American, that will lift the shuttle into the heavens. And may the hand of God bring it safely back to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>.'' `` And when the Discovery takes off, seven precious souls will soar beside it, the seven heroes of the Challenger,'' he added. `` With their lives, they moved a nation, they summoned <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to reach higher still, as they wrote man's destiny into the stars.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> recalled how he had joined Americans in mourning the loss of the Challenger crew members `` one cold January day'' in 1986, and said: `` We are a nation born of pioneers, and we will always create our future on the frontier. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can live no other way.''
