<HEAD>House Panels Approve Banking Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two House committees approved legislation Thursday that grants banks broad new powers to affiliate through holding companies with securities firms. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> and Judiciary committees, racing a deadline, approved amendments to a bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> last month. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> also has completed work on a separate measure. The Energy and <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, under Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., hastily approved amendments drafted by the panel late Wednesday night and early Thursday morning One amendment, which was being reproduced for members, arrived at the committee at 11:55 a.m. and was approved at 12:01 p.m. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said in a statement after 23 committee members voted to send the measure to the floor, with only Rep. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, D-Tex., asking that he be recorded against the bill: `` The committee today restored balance and equity to the restructuring of the financial services industry `` The real winners today were the nation's depositors, investors and taxpayers,'' he said. `` If everyone with an interest in this legislation, both inside and outside the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, can come together in a spirit of harmony and compromise, it will be possible to work out a bill.'' Treasury Undersecretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> issued a statement expressing `` strong opposition'' to the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s action. It `` demonstrates that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> is not prepared to move forward into the modern financial world ... -LRB- and is -RRB- retreating into a protectionist, anti-competitive regime left over from the 1930s,'' he said. The administration favors the bank-securities bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> because it permits banks to enter into a greater number of securities activities. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogilvie </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said, however, his organization is extremely disappointed by the action taken by the <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> committee. `` At a time when positive legislation is badly needed to modernize the banking laws so bankers can fully meet their customers' needs, the committee's action removes the only positive feature contained in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill _ new securities authorities,'' he said. `` Their action also makes the limited bank insurance authorities even more restrictive. If passed, the bill would be a dramatic step backwards for American consumers and <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. banking.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also approved the measure after removing mandatory prison sentences for individuals who breach the so-called `` firewalls'' constructed between banking and securities functions, an amendment introduced by Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N </LOCATION>. The full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is expected to take up the measure next week. In his opening statement, <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said any relaxation of the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act, designed to preclude virtually all securities activities by banks and their affiliates, `` must carry with it the creation of strong firewalls, functional regulation, and effective prohibitions against conflicts of interest in order to repeat the abuses which necessitated the creation of the Glass-Steagall wall.'' He said he believes his amendments do that. Among other things, the amendments would: _ Prohibit loans between banks and their securities affiliates to prop up a failing affiliate or purchase securities underwritten by the affiliate _ Strictly limit transfer of confidential customer information between banks and securities affiliates _ Prohibit illegal tie-ins so that all dealings are arms-length _ Prohibit a bank from stuffing its trust department accounts with unsound securities underwritten by its securities affiliate _ Prohibit shared name, premises, log and advertising _ Prohibit shared officers, directors and employees, with rulemaking authority to make exceptions for smaller banks
