<HEAD>Accused Detroit Crack Kingpins Go on Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Small-town youths awed by easy money were used to build a major big-city drug empire in what a federal prosecutor Thursday called `` A Tale of Two Cities'' _ rural <PERSON> Marianna </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, and cocaine-infested <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. Cocaine, processed in `` cook-up houses'' by 14-year-old girls into crack, its smokeable form, was sold by boys, many under 16, in crack houses run by the Chambers ring, which once accounted for half of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s crack trade, prosecutors charge. Four Chambers brothers _ <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Marlowe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> _ and 10 other people are on trial on federal charges including cocaine conspiracy, firearms and tax evasion counts. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said in opening arguments that <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> came from <LOCATION> Marianna </LOCATION> in 1982 and built their empire on three secrets of success: recruiting, organization and discipline. <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>' first witness, former organization member <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Middleton </PERSON>, backed his descriptions of an expanding network of trusted lieutenants and child drug dealers, kept in line by a no-holds-barred `` wrecking crew or beat-up crew.'' Fourteen defendants, their attorneys, prosecutors and reporters outnumbered spectators in a small federal courtroom for the opening day of an expected six-week trial. Jury selection took four days. People passed through a metal detector to enter, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals sat at both ends of the hallway in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s federal building. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Coonce </PERSON>, agent in charge of the <