<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> was stopped as he left the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday to hear an appeal from an Armenian dissident who wants to visit his ailing mother. <PERSON> Amvarsam </PERSON> <PERSON> Khlgatian </PERSON>, 61, had been waiting for two hours across the street carrying a placard that read, `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, Let Me Visit My Dying Mother,'' while <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> met inside with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. As the motorcade started for the Soviet embassy, <PERSON> Khlgatian </PERSON> dashed into the street carrying his placard. The motorcade stopped and startled security agents wrestled Khlgatian to the ground. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> left his limousine to talk to the demonstrator for a few minutes. `` He said, ` Do n't worry, I ` ll take care of it','' <PERSON> Khlgatian </PERSON> said afterward. `` But he can do nothing. It's up to the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Khlgatian </PERSON> said he made a similar appeal to <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> a few months ago `` and he said the same thing.'' The protester said he was exiled from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1979 after serving 15 years in labor camps for attempting to escape to the West. He said he works as a machinist in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khlgatian </PERSON> gave <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> a leaflet in which he described his mother as 80 years old and fatally ill. It said General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, despite promises of humanization, had kept him from visiting her in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the Armenian capital. `` For me, no matter who was and who is on the top, there was n't and is n't justice on the bottom,'' the leaflet said It concluded with an appeal for help. Later, returning for another session with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, the Soviet foreign minister said he had never met the demonstrator before. Asked about his appeal, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said: `` I am looking into it. ... This is the human approach.''
