<HEAD>Summer Goes into Overtime on Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The northern border states had a chilly afternoon Thursday, but summer remained in full throttle across the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> region, even as fall officially began at 3:29 p.m. EDT. Temperatures of 90 to 95 degrees with high humidity extended across <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to eastern portions of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. A cooler air mass along the Canadian border kept afternoon temperatures in the 50s and 60s in northern states. Dividing the two air masses, a frontal system extended across <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, the central Plains and the central <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>. Showers and thunderstorms were scattered to the north of the front from the southern Great Lakes to the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. The strongest thunderstorms early Thursday afternoon were developing over northern <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and in parts of southern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. A few showers also occurred over the northern and <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included about a half-inch at <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> and at <LOCATION> Muskegon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; and about a third of an inch at <LOCATION> Lansing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>; and Grand Rapids, <LOCATION> Mich </LOCATION>.. Across the front in the central Plains, there were sharp temperature contrasts At 2 p.m. CDT, <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, had 67 degrees while <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, about 150 miles away, had 93 degrees. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 47 degrees at <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, to 95 degrees at <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. The low in the nation Thursday morning was 22 degrees at <LOCATION> Truckee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. For Friday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> across the northern and central Appalachians, the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> Showers and thunderstorms should be most numerous in northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and portions of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state and western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms were expected in central and southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and from the central <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION> to the central high Plains. Light rain was predicted near the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> coast. High temperatures were forecast to be in the 70s and 80s across most of the nation. Highs should be in the 90s in much of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valleys </LOCATION>, the Gulf Coast states, the southern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coastal </LOCATION> states and in the desert <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>. Temperatures should only reach the 6