<HEAD>South Africa Bans Anti-Apartheid Conference</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with conference ban, reports fifth man
turned away by consulate, State Department comment. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Thursday banned a national anti-apartheid conference planned for this weekend, and a fourth activist took refuge in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulate </ORGANIZATION> after escaping from detention. Organizers had depicted the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> conference as one of the most important anti-apartheid gatherings in 30 years. More than 70 groups, with members ranging from black militants to liberal white Parliament members, had planned to discuss strategies for countering repression of dissent. The ban was part of a crackdown on opposition. Earlier Thursday, authorities backed off in the case of the latest escape by a detainee, who joined three other anti-apartheid activists holed up at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Consulate. Police issued, then withdrew an arrest warrant for <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON>, who escaped Wednesday while being treated at a hospital and fled to the 11th-floor consulate in a downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> office building. Consular officials allowed <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON> to remain while his case is assessed, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavis </PERSON> said. The consular officials earlier provided refuge for three prominent activists who escaped Sept. 13. <PERSON> Zavis </PERSON> said he could not confirm reports that the consulate turned away a fifth fugitive Wednesday night. Local news reports said a black man sought by police was refused entry into the consulate and later was taken into custody under security legislation. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Thursday that the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> given refuge agreed not to have contact with news media as a condition of their staying. This was so the consulate could continue normal operations and avoid activities incompatible with diplomatic activity, he said. Black activist <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> visited the consulate Wednesday and complained that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials would not let the detainees contact reporters. Police pledged not to arrest the three initial escapees if they leave the consulate, but Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> confirmed that a multipronged crackdown against other activists is under way. Across <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, more than two dozen activists were detained or barred from political activities this week, offices of anti-apartheid groups were raided, and pedestrians and motorists in urban centers were subjected to random searches. Brig. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mellet </PERSON>, spokesman for <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, announced the conference ban. He said one goal of the conference was to promote disruption of upcoming nationwide municipal elections. Activists advocate a boycott of the elections, saying the segregated black council seats at stake are components of a white-controlled system that excludes blacks from central government. <PERSON> Mellet </PERSON> said participants in the conference were sympathetic to the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement and were seeking to fill the vaccuum created by the banning in February of 17 major anti-apartheid groups. The groups included the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a nationwide coalition. The crackdown comes during an upsurge of bombings, including five in a 9-hour span late Wednesday and early Thursday. Authorities said 38 people were injured, including 18 whites at a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> bus terminal and 19 blacks at a disco on the other side of the city. The disco owner said three white men left shortly before the blast without drinking their beer. Police have blamed most recent bombings on the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>. But activists believe right-wing vigilantes or a covert security force unit carried out the recent bombing of a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> building used by anti-apartheid groups. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Ngcobo </PERSON>: `` He indicates that he is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and had been in detention for five months prior to his escape. He is now in temporary refuge with the three other ... activists.'' The three are <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Morobe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Valli </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosa </PERSON>, leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> UDF </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Vusi </PERSON> <PERSON> Khanyile </PERSON>, chairman of the banned <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crisis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
