<HEAD>Precede JERUSALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Troops Wound 24 Palestinian Rioters; Cement Hurled At Rabin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATING Palestinian casualties. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, Also Thursday ...; SUBS grafs 9-10, Twelve Palestinians
... with 3 grafs of detail. Picks up 11th graf pvs, Rabin credited
... with minor editing to trim. ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHAN YUNIS, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Troops fired live ammunition and plastic bullets to put down widespread Palestinian demonstrations Thursday, including an attack by masked, ax-wielding youths. Twenty-four Palestinians were wounded, Arab hospital officials said. Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> escaped injury during a tour of the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> town of <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yunis </PERSON> when a Palestinian assailant hurled a chunk of cement from a nearby rooftop. Soldiers rushed to the site but made no arrests. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said mass arrests of grass-roots activists in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> succeeded in curbing large-scale riots, but added: `` Have we succeeded in bringing stone throwing to a standstill? Not yet.'' <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said he did not see the rock hurled Thursday but said about 80 percent of the violence in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> involved stone-throwing. Also Thursday, the army said four soldiers would face trial in the beating death of an elderly <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> man, <PERSON> Khader </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarazi </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>'s Jabaliya refugee camp. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said they were to be charged with manslaughter. It said the soldiers struck the man with clubs after they broke into his home Aug. 22 to arrest Palestinian youths suspected of throwing stones. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, dozens of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> youths marched through the casbah, or market, chanting anti-Israeli slogans, waving <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flags and holding pictures of <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, an army spokesman said. The youths wore Arab headscarves wrapped around their faces and garbage bags over their clothes to hide their identities. They attacked troops with rocks and axes. Soldiers responded with plastic bullets and live ammunition, an army spokeswoman said. Sixteen Palestinians were wounded in the clash, including a 12-year-old shot in the right hand and two 16-year-olds hit in the stomach, officials at <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>' <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ittihad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> said. They said four other Palestinians were wounded in clashes in villages near <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>. Other Arab hospital officials said four Palestinians were wounded in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, including a 13-year-old boy who was shot in the chest and rushed to <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hashomer </LOCATION> hospital in serious condition. Acording to the army and to a military spokesman, 11 Palestinians were wounded in <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> and nearby <LOCATION> Burka </LOCATION> village and three were wounded in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, including one listed in serious condition. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> credited the use of plastic bullets against stone throwers for a recent upsurge in casualties and said they reduced violence in the territories. According to army orders, troops can fire plastic bullets at the legs of stone throwers even if soldiers' lives are not in danger. Unlike live ammunition, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials say plastic bullets are not generally lethal when fired at a distance of 20 yards or more. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> also said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would never relinquish control over the occupied territories to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> before peace negotiations as demanded by <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> last week in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` I would like to clarify that all the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> talk abou