on supporters to step up sabotage of vehicles that ignored the measure. The guerrillas also stepped up sabotaging power transmission lines in several of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s 14 provinces. Bus and truck traffic returned to normal during morning rush hour. The rebels' clandestine <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venceremos </ORGANIZATION> said the ban _ the fifth this year _ was lifted as of midnight Wednesday. At least three vehicles were burned during the ban, which reduced bus and truck traffic in the capital by about 70 percent. Traffic on provincial highways was almost completely paralyzed. Some buses and trucks that operated since Monday covered their license plates trying to avoid reprisals. The guerrillas blew up about 35 utility posts or high-tension wire towers after the transport ban began, military sources said. Four eastern provinces were without electricity early Thursday because of overnight sabotage.
