<HEAD>Hurricane Helene Strengthens, But Still No Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with 10:30 p.m. position, track.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane <PERSON> Helene </PERSON>'s winds strengthened to 110 mph in the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> on Thursday, but forecasters said the storm was still no threat to land. At 10:30 p.m. EDT, the center of the 250-mile wide storm was at latitude 14.1 north and longitude 44.3 west, or about 1,020 miles east of the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> was moving west-northwest at 10 mph and was expected to continue that track and speed through Thursday. `` This is a very good hurricane _ it's already something to reckon with,'' <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> forecaster <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> said. `` But the currents suggest it is going to turn to the north _ it's just too early to speculate.'' Air currents from a low pressure trough over the ocean may draw <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> northward into the open <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, away from the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> islands and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> showed signs of northwest movement by late Thursday. But if it heads into the eastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, islands could be affected by early next week, said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>. In the meantime, <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> was growing stronger and more organized as it moved westward across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> from its spawning grounds near the the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> off the African coast. <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> is the eighth named storm of the 1988 Atlantic hurricane season. Storms become hurricanes when sustained winds reach a minimum 74 mph. Of the season's three previous hurricanes, <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> swept across the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, killing hundreds, but the other two, <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Debby </PERSON>, caused only minor damage in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>.
