N> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> and seven other diplomats the Sandinista government expelled on July 11. The Sandinista government accused the diplomats of trying to destabilize the country. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in turn expelled Nicaraguan Ambassador <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Tunnerman </PERSON> and seven of his colleagues. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> family members, his doctor, chief of protocol and many of his senior advisers were among the 22 to 25 Nicaraguans whose visas were not processed in time for the Sept. 28 address, <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> said. The Sandinista government protested `` the unjustified delay'' in issuing the visas, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> communique broadcast over state-run radio Wednesday night. It said <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s representatives to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and the Organization of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had been instructed to `` intercede before the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> so that without major delays the visas in question are granted.'' The statement said the state of U.S.-Nicaraguan relations should not be a factor in the issuance of the visas. `` In adopting this type of attitude, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> clearly ignores those commitments it has assumed as the host country of international organizations, specifically violating existing stipulations in the agreement between the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> relative to the site of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement said. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> told the Nicaraguan mission that <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and some senior Nicaraguan officials would have received their visas in time for their scheduled arrival Friday, <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> said on Wednesday. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also told the Nicaraguan Mission that the other 22 to 25 visas would not be decided until Oct. 4, a week after <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> was to speak to the 159-member <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since 1981 has supported rebels seeking to overthrow <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> has said that in addition to refusing replacements for <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> and the seven other expelled diplomats, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> is not issuing visas to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats assigned to replace envoys being routinely reassigned or to personnel seeking to visit the embassy on official business.
