<HEAD>U.N. Chief Says Peace In South-West Africa Closer Than Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW TORCHIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said Thursday that independence is `` closer than ever'' for <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The territory, commonly known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, is <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s last colony and has been ruled by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in defiance of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> resolutions. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> arrived early Thursday on his first visit to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since 1983 to discuss recent regional peace initiatives which have revived the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s 10-year-old plan for Namibian independence. `` We are closer than ever to a solution to the problem,'' the Peruvian diplomat said at a cocktail party after a day of talks with Namibian and South African officials. `` We hope that in the very near future you will have next to our country a sister republic, the republic of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>,'' he said. Earlier, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> met for more than two hours with Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>. Both emerged to say progress had been made. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> was host of the subsequent reception, attended by more than 200 guests of all races at a former presidential residence in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. `` I would be kidding you if I said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> was a popular concept in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> told <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> at the reception. `` But it is a privilege to have you here.'' <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has agreed to end its 73-year rule over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and allow <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observers to oversee the transition to independence, but only if the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops in neighboring <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> withdraw. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has agreed in principle to withdraw its troops, but there is dispute over the timetable. U.S.-mediated talks involving <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, aimed at setting this timetable, are to resume Monday in <LOCATION> Brazzaville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>. Most opposition parties in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> rejected an invitation by <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> to come to <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> for consultations, but members of the territory's transitional, multiracial Cabinet met with him for more than an hour Thursday. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> was scheduled to meet President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> on Friday, then travel to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> for talks with leaders of its Marxist government.
</TEXT>
