<HEAD>Export Labor a Main Source of Foreign Currency for Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With jobs scarce at home, so many Filipinos have gone to work abroad that they have become one of their country's main sources of foreign currency and a key factor in keeping the economy going. Hundreds of thousands leave each year and many of them are trained workers who take jobs far below their capabilities because of the higher pay abroad. Teachers, for example, work as maids overseas because the wages are much higher than a teacher's salary at home. Even so, President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> calls these export workers the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> `` new heroes.'' The estimated 1.5 million to 2.5 million overseas contract workers remain a steady source of income for the country's faltering economy Overseas workers sent home $ 791.9 million in 1987, making them the country's third largest source of foreign exchange after exports of electronic components and garments. <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> figures indicate that foreign-worker remittances for the first half of 1988 totaled $ 419.3 million. The money does n't go directly to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> government but the government benefits by its flowing into the economy. In general, the workers send some of their foreign wages home to their families. The families exchange the foreign currencies at banks or other financial houses for <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> pesos. The foreign currencies then circulate through the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> financial system. The currencies might be purchased by a <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> importer, for example, to buy foreign goods or by the government to pay off part of the nation's foreign debt. <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Achacoso </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> POEA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, says 450,000 workers with contracts approved by his agency left for work abroad last year. That does not include uncounted thousands who leave without seeking help from the <ORGANIZATION> POEA </ORGANIZATION>. Those with <ORGANIZATION> POEA </ORGANIZATION> approved contracts included 60,000 maids, some of whom left skilled professions in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> to work as domestics abroad. <PERSON> Achacoso </PERSON> said the exodus has left shortages in some key skills at home. Shipping companies, for example, say they have problems finding skippers for ferry boats in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> archipelago as well as crews for domestic oil and chemical tankers. Nurses are also in short supply, `` and pretty soon, we might have a shortage of computer experts or programmers,'' Achacoso said. But Achacoso denies there has been a `` brain drain,'' and he said the foreign exchange earnings outweigh the disadvantages are. `` You ca n't speak of a brain drain because most of these people do not have jobs here,'' he said. `` Those who were employed here and left, simply opened up positions for the unemployed here.'' President <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> told Filipino maids in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> last April that overseas workers helped reduce the unemployment rate to about 9 percent and if they had remained at home, `` you could have been part of that statistic.'' The worker exodus began in the mid-1970's when <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> oil countries hired thousands of foreigners to build roads, office buildings, hotels and homes and to manage new development projects. Even though the oil boom has faded, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> remains the major destination of Filipino workers. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> alone employs at least 300,000 of them as nurses, office clerks, public transport drivers, janitors and as private servants. Families of overseas workers often are the only ones with money to build homes or buy new appliances in rural areas. But overseas workers sometimes suffer abuses. `` The problems are with those who go there as tourists,'' he said. `` The moment their visas expire, they are open to a lot of abuses, and they can range from rape to being forced into prostitution, non-payment of salaries and being beaten up.'' <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Catequista </PERSON>, a 31-year-old accountant, recently applied for a job abroad with <ORGANIZATION> POEA </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'd like office work _ clerical, bookkeeping, anything,'' he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He added that he had earned 2,500 pesos -LRB- $ 125 -RRB- a month at a local bank until it closed in 1985. He has since been earning about the same amount selling encyclopedias because he can not find a steady job. <PERSON> Josefina </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahilga </PERSON>, 38, who trained as a teacher, took a job as a maid abroad after she could not find a teaching post and ended up earning 2,000 pesos -LRB- $ 100 -RRB- a month rolling cigarettes in a tobacco factory. As a maid in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, she earns the equivalent of $ 450 a month plus free board and lodging and has seen much of the world. Before coming home on for a six-month leave, she joined her German employer on a family ski vacation in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. Others cite reasons beyond economics for working abroad. `` It's always the money _ and going to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said a former X-ray technician who works as a maid in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. `` They always think it will be easier to get to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from -LRB- other countries -RRB- than from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Sept. 30</NOTE>
