<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-22 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0527</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer prices rose at a 5.2 percent annual rate in August as a result of higher food, shelter and gasoline prices, the government reports. Food and beverage prices rose 0.5 percent for the month, compared with 0.9 percent in July, when the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the greatest impact of the dry weather in the Farm Belt began reaching consumer pocketbooks. But gasoline prices jumped a whopping 3 percent in August, the biggest increase in 12 months, the department said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans' personal income increased only half as fast as inflation in August, the government says in a new report. The numbers released Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> are consistent with other recent government reports showing the economy slowed in August from its vigorous pace during the first half of the year. Personal income grew 0.2 percent, while personal consumption spending rose 0.5 percent. A price index tied to the personal income report rose 0.4 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
