 OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members and a possible reduction in the cartel's oil output. Recent reports have suggested that several <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> countries are producing far above their assigned quotas, helping to flood world markets with oil and keeping prices weak. Nevertheless, near-month contracts for crude oil and gasoline continued to gain strength from falling inventories in the face of strong demand. Oil brokers said demand is up nearly 2 percent from last year. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil stocks were down by 6.212 million barrels in the week ended Sept. 16, while gasoline stocks fell by 2.58 million barrels. Analysts said the fall in gasoline inventories stemmed from last week's hurricane in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the temporary shutdown of several refineries in the area.
