<SECOND>PM-Stock Disputes, Bjt,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass. Bans Mandatory Arbitration Between Stockbrokers, Investors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The securities industry is expected to mount a constitutional challenge to new <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> regulations designed to protect small investors by barring agreements that prevent investors from suing their stockbrokers. Responding to a flood of investor complaints after last year's stock market crash, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> today becomes the first state to ban such agreements The new regulations outlaw contracts that require arbitration in disputes over losses. Securities industry officials say <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> is treading on thin constitutional ice in enacting the guidelines because the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last year upheld contracts that make arbitration agreements a precondition for doing business. `` Any lender has preconditions on what terms they lend you money,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON>, general counsel of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday. `` It's not unreasonable to say if we have a dispute we're not going to go through the very expensive and inefficient method of litigation.'' <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON>, who testified against the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> rule at a July hearing, predicted securities industry groups would sue the state over the mandatory arbitration ban. Officials said 16 other states are planning similar regulations. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' new rules, to be filed today by the secretary of state's office, take effect Jan. 1, 1989. `` We're concerned about investors having a choice,'' said Deputy Secretary of State <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meehan </PERSON>. `` We do n't want them to be in a position where they have no choice but to sign away their day in court.'' Most brokerage firms require customers to settle disputes through an arbitration hearing sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> or other market organizations. Arbitration is cheaper and faster than suing, but investors have only a limited right to appeal. While big institutional investors can negotiate contracts with brokerages, individual investors usually have little choice but to agree, often unknowingly, to arbitration. A <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> survey this year of 65 firms handling 90 percent of all customer accounts found virtually all require arbitration, particularly for customers who borrow money from the firm through margin accounts or trade in risky stock options. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> officials said they have received hundreds of complaints since the Oct. 19 market crash from disgruntled investors who did n't realize they had waived their right to sue for losses. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> said it received 1,175 arbitration cases through August compared with 616 for the same period of 1987 and a total of 1,000 for all last year. Securities lawyers said mandatory arbitration agreements often are buried in `` boilerplate gobbledygook'' of contracts in sections on margin accounts or options. `` I know of very few industries that try to incorporate such restrictions in their agreements or have been allowed to do that to such an extent,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantwell </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, securities lawyer who opposes mandatory arbitration. <PERSON> Cantwell </PERSON> said the market crash led to more investor complaints only because people started losing money. `` One, two, three years before the crash, a lot of improper practices by brokers simply went unnoticed or would n't be focused on by investigators because things were going well,'' he said. In addition to the state action, a bill introduced in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in July would make it illegal for a broker to turn away a customer's business for refusing to sign an arbitration clause and would reform the arbitration process. `` It would probably be more beneficial if the arbitration system itself was fairer and took into consideration the customer's point of view more frequently than it does now,'' said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, editor of the journal of the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts say the system favors brokers because investors are allowed a limited number of challenges and arbitration boards generally consist of former securities officials and can be insensitive to small investors' concerns. `` Arbitration remains and probably will remain the primary dispute resolution for customers with complaints against their brokers,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of state regulators. `` But that does n't mean it should be exclusive or individuals should be denied their fundamental rights.'' The association said the number of its arbitration cases quintupled from 800 in 1980 to 4,100 last year and could climb above 6,000 this year. But <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> said only a very small percentage of complaints to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> are about arbitration. He said most brokerage firms do n't require customers with cash accounts to sign arbitration clauses and customers who want to borrow money on margin can go to banks or elsewhere. According to the secretary of state's office, the 16 other states planning to impose similar regulations are: <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>.
