<SECOND>PM-Farm Review-Equipment,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Equipment Sales Down, But Cautious Optimism For 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Financial uncertainty caused by the drought are forcing farmers to hold off buying new machinery for their fields, dashing hopes for a banner year in the farm equipment industry, according to some salesmen. `` This year will certainly slow down next year, maybe not as much, but there wil be a cloud hanging over us. It takes a lot of years for a farmer to recover a loss,'' said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Hennessey </PERSON>, a territory manager for <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Idea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Coldwater </LOCATION>. `` Normally, they'll trade it in on a 3-5 year basis, and this would've been the greatest fall in eight years. But then the drought hit and delayed their opportunity to buy,'' said B.E. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, southern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> marketing manager for Case IH. <PERSON> Hennessey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> were among approximately 500 commercial exhibitors at the three-day Farm Science Review, which ends Thursday. The agricultural exposition included about $ 40 million worth of farm equipment. The number of hours a farmer uses a tractor varies, but Case's C.L <PERSON> Lephart </PERSON> said an average for a cash grain farmer would be about 250 hours a year. Normally, a farmer may trade that in after five years, but now they are allowing their equipment to depreciate and trading it in with as many as 7,000 hours on it. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said this year's drought was a particular letdown because analysts finally were anticipating a good year after years of a depressed farm economy. `` They'd finally got their debt load paid off, which would've permitted them to come back and buy, but now ...'' said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, his voice trailing off <PERSON> Lephart </PERSON>, Case marketing manager for northwest <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, said the drought led to a new marketing plan. `` Discounts, financing, leases. We're seeing a lot more of all of these,'' <PERSON> Lephart </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> parts marketing manager <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hothem </PERSON> said the company hopes to cash in on a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> projection that there will be as many as 25 million new acres to till next year. While equipment sales have been slow, a different type of machinery has moved out of the storerooms and onto the farms. Tillage equipment, such as field cultivators, have sold better than usual `` because no-tillage did n't work out,'' <PERSON> Hennessey </PERSON> said, referring to a farming method aimed at soil conservation `` Conventional and mechanical tillage is coming back into play,'' <PERSON> Lepart </PERSON> said. Lepart and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> think 1989 will be a better year for sales, but say they wo n't be able to put profits into perspective until all crops are harvested. `` There's certainly a lot of room for optimism,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. The Farm Science Review, on the 992-acre <ORGANIZATION> Molly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caren </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, about 25 miles west of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, included field demonstrations and exhibits by farm equipment manufacturers and dealers. The annual agribusiness exposition is sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>.
