<SECOND>BC-US-Europe Trade,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Says United States, EEC Far Apart on Meat Hormones,
Airbus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its European trading partners remain far apart on solving disputes over a ban on hormone-treated meat and support for civil aircraft development, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said Thursday. But <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingon </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference that trade relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the 12-nation European trading bloc are `` actually pretty good.'' `` We have succeeded in the last year and a half of cleaning the table of most of the troublesome trade issues that existed some two years ago between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the community,'' he said. Trade between the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will likely exceed more than $ 160 billion this year, up from $ 145 billion in 1987 and $ 131 billion in 1986, <PERSON> Kingon </PERSON> said. Two key disputes remaining, he said, are European enforcement of a ban on meat from animals treated with growth hormones and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> objections to government support for <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrie </ORGANIZATION>, a four-nation European consortium that competes with <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kingon </PERSON> said little progress has been made on either issue and no resolution was in sight The meat hormone dispute, he said, `` is perhaps the most difficult problem on the table.'' An <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said, `` No new initiative can be expected from the -LRB- community -RRB- on hormones. There is a deadlock.'' The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> says it wants to ban imports of all hormone-treated meat for health reasons. Late last year, it decided to delay implementation of the ban until Jan. 1, 1989. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had threatened to take retaliatory action if the ban was imposed. It contends the use of hormones to fatten animals, which is a common practice among American farmers, is not a health risk. <PERSON> Kingon </PERSON> predicted the issue would wind up in the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, an international body that solves disputes between trading partners. On the Airbus issue, <PERSON> Kingon </PERSON> said negotiations were continuing. But, he said, `` I would not want to mislead you to say we are close to a solution because we're not.'' A key objective of U.S.-European negotiations has been to set `` effective discipline'' on new infusions of capital and on the conditions under which government support may be provided to future civil aircraft programs. The four governments involved in the Airbus program are <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is made up of <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
