<HEAD>SEC Said to Authorizes Civil Charges Against New York Bond House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has authorized its staff to charge <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Wright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and several officers of the bond house with fraud and other abuses in connection with the underwriting of more than $ 1 billion in municipal bonds, the Wall Street Journal reported Thursday. Quoting what it called people familiar with the situation, the newspaper said the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> took the unannounced step at a closed-door meeting Tuesday. The reported action followed a major inquiry into the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> firm's activities. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> McCue </PERSON> declined comment on the Journal report, in accordance with the agency's policy on enforcement matters. But the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> had stated in a previously published notice that its agenda for the Tuesday session included `` institution of administrative proceedings of an enforcement nature.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Aufhauser </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> attorney, was not immediately available to comment, a receptionist said. The Journal quoted him as saying he'd had discussions with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> staff but could not elaborate. <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> has consistently denied wrongdoing and has asserted its underwriting practices conform with industry practices. The Journal quoted sources as saying the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> action means the agency's enforcement staff will enter into settlement negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. If those fail, the sources were quoted as saying, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> may charge the firm with a range of alleged abuses. Most of the charges stem from <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s role as an underwriter of 25 municipal bond deals in 1985 and 1986, the sources were quoted as saying. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> case does n't include the firm's best-known deals, $ 380 million in questionable issues underwritten for <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> and the Northern Mariana islands in 1984 and 1985, the newspaper quoted sources as saying. It was unclear why these were omitted, but the newspaper said it may have been because other government enforcement agencies are scrutinizing them. Last year a federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> charged <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Abba </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, the firm's executive vice president, with fraud, bribery and obstruction of justice. He's pleaded innocent and will go on trial in January. In August, the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> decreed that interest income on the <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> and Mariana bonds are n't tax-exempt. This is significant because the tax-exempt status of such issues is a major selling point of municipal bonds.
