<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-U.S.Sugar     09-22 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-U.S. Sugar,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Seeks International Trade Inquiry On U.S. Sugar Quotas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> will ask for an international trade inquiry into <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> restrictions on imports of sugar, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said. The Commission will make the request at a meeting Thursday of the Council of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the international trade organization meeting in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and studying ways to improve world trade relations. The panel will be asked to examine the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s contention that the long-standing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> import curbs are inconsistent with international trading rules, said the spokeswoman, who declined to be named. The EEC and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials had two inconclusive rounds of talks on the issue in July and early in September, she said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has imposed import restrictions on sugar, dairy products, peanuts and cotton for many years ince it was granted a waiver from international trade rules in 1955. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> contends that the protection enabled <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmers to build up their production of the commodities. Sugar production in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> rose to 5.4 million tons in 1986 from 4.2 million tons in 1955, according to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>. The spokeswoman said that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> import quota for sugar in 1988 amounted to 700,000 metric tons while the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> imported 4 million tons of sugar last year. The spokeswoman said that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> had similar complaints about the other products covered by the waiver but is still reviewing those cases. She also said that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> would express to the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> its concern about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade bill which it believes to be protectionist and potentially damaging for the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> round of international trade talks.
</TEXT>
