<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv23   09-22 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 23,0623</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday Sept. 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Diamonds in Copper and Iron Country</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: John Cunniff is on assignment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Two companies are trying to add some glitter to the drab copper and iron-ore mining scene of far northern <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. It started as a glint in a <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> metallurgist's eye. First Dow, and now a <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> company, <ORGANIZATION> Crystal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, entered the search for diamonds in the state's <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. Seven Kimberlite pipes _ volcanic rock shafts that can yield the earth's hardest mineral _ have been discovered. Core drilling has unearthed a scattering of sand-grain sized diamonds, too few and too small for commercial production. But the explorers say the search is young. The pipe formations are in a 40-mile area around <LOCATION> Iron </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> and Crystal Falls, at the western end of the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> along the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> border. In the few places on earth they are found, Kimberlite pipes occur in clusters of up to several dozen, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Huml </PERSON>, a Dow research associate. <PERSON> Huml </PERSON>, a metallurgist by trade and geologist by avocation, said he thinks there are more than a dozen Kimberlite pipes in the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. Dow has searched for six years. Now more exploration and mining expertise is needed, <PERSON> Huml </PERSON> said. `` Dow is not a hard-rock mining company.'' Dow recently sold its mineral leases and geological data, for an undisclosed amount, to <ORGANIZATION> Crystal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> subsidiary of <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Restech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>. Restech has mineral exploration and gold mining operations in western <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> It will carry on the search, while <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> holds onto an option to take part in the exploration and development, and to share in any profits. Occasional diamond finds in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> farm fields in the late 1800s and early 1900s long had geologists looking to the north, said <ORGANIZATION> Crystal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION>'s president, <PERSON> Sigfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Muessig </PERSON>. <PERSON> Muessig </PERSON> said a Kimberlite pipe, named for <PERSON> Kimberly </PERSON> in the diamond-mining region of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, is the only formation known to produce the gems. `` It is a cylindrical formation where volcanic rock has come up 120 miles from the bowels of the earth, and the heat and pressure have formed the diamonds,'' he said. `` It's a very rare occurrence,'' <PERSON> Huml </PERSON> said. Other Kimberlite pipes have been found in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. None commercially produce diamonds. There were no volcanic remnants in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, so geologists thought glaciers carried the diamonds there from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Muessig </PERSON> said. But he said the focus shifted in 1981 when the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey found a Kimberlite formation _ the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ellen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pipe </LOCATION> _ about 10 miles northeast of Crystal Falls. It was evidence that volcanoes smoked and spewed nearly 200 million years ago in the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, and possibly generated the heat and compression forces to leave a diamond treasure behind. The glaciers flattened the volcanoes, but since 1981 Dow has found six more Kimberlite pipes _ several hundred feet across at the surface and covered by volcanic debris, <PERSON> Huml </PERSON> said. In Dow's explorations, he said, `` We have found microdiamonds, generally small, less than a millimeter in diameter. They are grain-sized.'' But the explorers still think the western <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> was the source of the gems found in farm fields to the south. `` We think there is good potential, because of the historical finds,'' <PERSON> Muessig </PERSON> said. Crystal Exploration will do more sampling in the already discovered pipes in the next year, <PERSON> Muessig </PERSON> said, and will continue exploring for more Kimberlite formations, `` in hopes the next pipe we discover will have gem-quality stones.''
</TEXT>
