<HEAD>Northwest Airlines Rejects $200 Million Offer to Sell Land in
Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has rejected a $ 200 million offer from Japanese real estate developers to sell land it owns in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, officials of the airline said. Northwest officials declined Wednesday to discuss details of the purchase offer from <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> or say why it was rejected. `` We do n't have any property that's for sale,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>. But in a letter to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> real estate agent for <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vice </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> said the airline believes the land is worth more than has been offered and said it `` has been retained for possible further development by us in connection with our business in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.'' The developers wanted to build high-rise condominiums on the 50,000-square-foot plot, which would have been sold to property-starved <PERSON> Japa </PERSON> - nese consumers for $ 10 million to $ 15 million apiece <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION> hoped to place 60 to 65 units on the property. <ORGANIZATION> KOAR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Los Angeles-based real estate firm representing <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION>, said the property sought by <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION> contains five or six small two-story buildings that the airline uses to house employees, including flight crews and corporate staff members, on both a permanent and temporary basis. <ORGANIZATION> KOAR </ORGANIZATION> officials said the property is surrounded by exclusive residences, department stores and high-rise office buildings. Because of the scarcity of land and the density of the population in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, developers there are willing to buy property for $ 4,000 per square foot, which is the amount turned down by Northwest. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> would not describe the property and said <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> did not want to discuss its real estate holdings. <ORGANIZATION> KOAR </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> has owned the property for more than 30 years, which would mean that it obtained it at a fraction of the price it could fetch today. <ORGANIZATION> KOAR </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION> together own 366,600 shares of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> stock, which represents about 1.3 percent of outstanding shares. The price of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> stock rose 87.5 cents to $ 50.125 Wednesday, as news of the offer by <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION> circulated broadly among brokers. <ORGANIZATION> KOAR </ORGANIZATION> officials said <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION> has been trying to initiate discussions with <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> officials about a land deal since May to no avail. <ORGANIZATION> Koshin </ORGANIZATION> made its most recent all-cash offer two weeks ago, in which it `` implored <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> to act in its shareholders' best interests,'' said <ORGANIZATION> KOAR </ORGANIZATION> officials. Northwest responded Sept. 12 with a letter from <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>, which was provided to the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> KOAR </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON>, the newspaper said.
