<HEAD>SEC Rejects Enforcement Action In WPPSS Default</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS number of defendants, start of trial date, in 4th
graf; ADDS details throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> today announced that no enforcement action would be taken against those involved in the sale and default of $ 2.25 billion of <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> bonds. In a 376-page report on its five-year investigation, the commission staff criticized several parties involved in the sale of the WPPSS bonds, which were issued to finance two nuclear power projects that eventually were terminated. The report concluded that enforcement action was unnecessary because of a civil trial, difficulty in determining responsibility for disclosure statements attached to the bonds and concern that the commission lacked the resources to pursue the case. However, because of settlements in the civil trial, parties considered most responsible in the sale of the bonds will not be required to argue their cases in a public forum. Bondholders are suing 15 utilities that are members of <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, the construction arm of the state's public utilities, plus a financial advisor and two engineering firms in a trial that began Sept. 7 in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. Most parties originally named as defendants in the suit, including <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> itself, have settled out of court for a total of $ 461 million, including $ 96 million in contested insurance claims. The report concluded that the default, the largest in municipal bond history, resulted from extensive cost overruns and construction delays at <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> Project No. 4 at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation in southeastern <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state and No. 5 at Satsop, west of <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, which issued the bonds, was responsible for the official statements used to sell them but `` avoided disclosure of negative developments,'' the report said `` Most significantly, the supply system failed to disclose that, in October 1980, participants, who were concerned about rising project costs and falling power demands, asked the supply system to study a possible slowdown or termination of the projects.'' Work was halted on the projects in 1981, both were abandoned in January 1982 and in 1983 <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> quit making payments on the bonds after the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> held that the utilities' contracts with the consortium were illegal and thus unenforceable Without payments from the 88 participating utilities, many in other states, <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> defaulted. The commission report also faulted the <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> bond counsel, the firm of <ORGANIZATION> Wood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dawson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Hellman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which was responsible for assuring that the disclosures accompanying the bond sales were clear on the requirements that participating utilities pay for the projects. `` Although opinions on legal issues frequently contain some uncertainty, the state of the law was not as clear as those relying on the counsel's opinions might reasonably have assumed,'' the report said. `` Further steps were not taken to clarify legal matters.'' <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> settled outside court in the federal trial in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> for $ 500,000. Bond underwriters, including some of the largest brokerage houses on Wall Street, also were `` in a position to discover inadequacies'' in the disclosures, the report said. `` They did not, however, conduct the kind of investigation in the offerings of these competitively bid bonds that they perform in negotiated bond sales and in corporate securities offerings,'' the report said. Bond underwriters settled in the massive lawsuit for $ 92 million. Despite the size of that settlement, representatives of the 24,000 bond buyers with claims in the federal lawsuit said it was less than the profit of the underwriting firms in selling the WPPSS bonds. Besides the 15 utilities, defendants in the trial include the firm of <ORGANIZATION> Blyth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION>, financial advisor to <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, and the construction engineering firms of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Constructors and <ORGANIZATION> Ebasco </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
