<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices opened narrowly mixed today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> with little news in the market to influence prices. Soybean futures posted slight gains at the opening in reaction to a Soviet newspaper report that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s grain harvest this year would be smaller than the relatively good harvests of the two previous years. But soybeans quickly turned lower on reports of beneficial rain in the soybean-growing region of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and selling linked to the advancing corn and soybean harvest in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Harvest pressure is overhanging the grain markets as well, limiting the potential for strong rallies, analysts said. `` There really is not much of a story developing,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The harvest is progressing and in general the market is a little bit tired.'' In early trading, wheat was 1 \ cents to 2 cents lower with the contract for delivery in December at $ 4.21 \ a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1 -LCB- cents lower with December at $ 2.86 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at $ 2.55 a bushel; soybeans were 3 -LCB- cents lower to \ cent higher with November at $ 8.36 -LCB- a Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .18 cent higher with October at 69.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent lower to .15 cent higher with September at 