<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Sept. 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>Three Years After Plaza Accord, Currency Markets Still Unsettled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: John Cunniff is on assignment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Today marks the third anniversary of the Plaza Accord, a five-nation agreement that might be described as the Kellogg-Briand Pact of the financial world. The Kellogg-Briand Pact of 1928 was an international agreement to renounce war as an instrument of national policy. In light of subsequent conflicts _ World War II comes immediately to mind _ Kellogg-Briand was a miserable failure. The Plaza Accord of Sept. 22, 1985, was an agreement by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to push down the exchange value of the dollar. The idea was that a cheaper dollar would help shrink the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit and reduce protectionist sentiments in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. At first, the Plaza Accord looked like a smash success. The dollar tumbled all through 1985 and 1986 and into 1987. Only a few impolite skeptics said the dollar would have fallen even without the accord. Then, some funny things happened. First, the finance ministers got together again at the <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in February 1987 and decided that further declines in the dollar would be counterproductive. Naturally, the dollar kept falling. Then it rose. Then it fell steeply at the end of 1987. This year it has risen _ up a fat 14 percent against a marketbasket of foreign currencies since Jan. 1. In light of these gyrations, it has begun to seem as though the finance leaders are standing at the bow of an ocean liner with a toy wheel, trying to convince the other passengers they are steering. All this time, people began to notice the cheaper dollar was not working wonders on the trade deficit. Instead of shrinking, the gap set records in 1986 and again in 1987. It has taken until this year to see big improvements. As time went on, it has become increasingly clear that: 1. Central bankers and finance ministers do n't have much control over currency rates. 2. Currency rates do not have nearly as much to do with trade balances as everyone had thought. This is not to say the 3-year-old Plaza Accord was a waste of time. It was a valuable beginning toward cooperation in an interdependent world. But this is where the comparison with Kellogg-Briand comes in. In 1985 as in 1928, agreements between nations depend on the signatories' willingness to adapt their national goals to the greater international good. And that is a hard sell. Currency rates will never be stable as long as nations pursue widely differing economic policies: abhorrence of inflation in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> vs. relative tolerance of it in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, for example. The gold standard for currencies forced policy coordination on the nations, but its fatal flaw was that it put all the burden of adjustment on weak-currency countries. That gave undue leverage to the slow-growth West Germanys of the world. Businesses want stable currency rates so they can plan where to locate plants, how much to manufacture for export, from which nations to buy components and so on. Three years after the Plaza Accord, however, the goal of stable currencies is beginning to look like a distant dream. Economists' estimates of the `` proper'' value of the dollar are all over the map, from 100 yen to 200 yen -LRB- the current rate is 134 -RRB- Differing economic policies have something to do with the instability, as do differing predictions for the trade deficit. Adding to the complexity is that trade flows are not the only controlling factor in rates. Investment flows are at least as important _ meaning that if Japanese for whatever reason crave <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury bonds and factories, they will keep the dollar in strong demand even though they have little interest in importing American products. Stabilize currencies? Abolish war? Good luck.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday Sept. 22</NOTE>
