<HEAD>Irving, Bank of New York `Celebrate' 1st Anniversary Of Takeover
War</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 1.2 billion bid for rival <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has staggered to the one-year mark with neither side ready to throw in the towel, or even call the outcome. At first, it had the distinction of being the first-ever hostile takeover fight between two big American banks. Now it has become the lengthiest such battle among major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations. The strain of the bidding marathon clearly has taken its toll at both large <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> institutions by distracting management from their usual work, confusing stockholders and piling up millions of dollars in legal and other expenses. A third, friendly contender, Milan-based <ORGANIZATION> Banca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerciale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Italiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, recently was forced out of the running due to an unfavorable ruling by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which is patiently overseeing the proposed merger process. `` It's the economic equivalent of the Iran-Iraq war because of the length and the substantial casualties,'' said <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>. `` At least we're not using poison gas,'' the bank's chairman, <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON>, said jokingly in a recent interview. `` Only ` poison pills' are involved.'' The outcome of the Irving-Bank of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> war, which began on Sept. 25, 1987, is likely to be decided in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state court, where, among other things, <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s `` poison pill'' anti-takeover defense is under attack. Some observers say the entire process could drag on into the winter. In the meantime, the takeover attempt appears to have turned into a struggle of personalities between <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> and <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s equally strong-minded chairman, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> A. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>. Analysts say <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> is determined to merge the two banks not only because the two would fit nicely together but because he fears <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> itself could become a takeover target if a big <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> or foreign bank decided to enter the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market. A merger would nearly double <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s size, making it the 11th largest banking company in the country and a more elusive target. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, analysts say, has his own vision of running his bank and believes it is worth much more than the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s offer, especially given its past investments in technological advances. Both men have held only a handful of face-to-face meetings since <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> formally proposed the merger, and each time talks have broken off without any signs of progress. No new talks are planned because, <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said, `` we see absolutely nothing to be gained at this stage.'' `` I think the financial issues were certainly important to Irving early on and now, but ... it clearly has become a personal issue,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON>, a banking analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, a partner of <ORGANIZATION> Sullivan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Cromwell </LOCATION>, which has represented many firms in takeovers, agreed. `` My own judgment is that they have created this fiction that the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> is evil and horrible ... It's almost a crusade.'' That is an unfortunate turn of events, many analysts contend, since both banks have similar markets and services and would work well together. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> has waged a tough defense to <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s persistent overtures, from poison pills to proxy fights A recently instituted `` flip-in'' provision to its poison pill would make an unsolicited merger prohibitively expensive by giving all <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> shareholders, except <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, the right to buy $ 400 of stock for $ 200 once <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> acquires 20 percent of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>. `` The Irving board has taken enough action of a defensive nature and the burden is now on them to be able to show that they are not merely trying to entrench themselves and <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s management,'' said <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nad </PERSON>, publisher of the monthly newsletter Directorship, an authority on corporate boards. `` That's a very fine line to walk.'' <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> says he first broached the idea of a merger at a luncheon with <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> about five years ago. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> was n't very receptive then, he recalled. He conceded that <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> probably `` resents the fact we put an offer on the table like that'' after it had turned down the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> privately. What's particularly noteworthy about this battle is that it's occurring in an industry where hostile takeovers are rare Even in the best of circumstances, the complex, time-consuming regulatory requirements that other industries are spared could make some banks think twice about a merger. When the bid first emerged, some experts predicted hostile bids could become more commonplace, particularly among aggressive regional institutions. They're not so sure anymore. `` Hostile takeovers have no place in banking,'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said recently. `` They are a severe threat to the stability of the banking industry and the soundness of the economy.'' New ground, though, was broken on the regulatory front. For one thing, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> declined to make any distinction between a friendly or hostile offer in approving <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s application in February. And in August, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> decided to treat foreign owners of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks much the same as domestic owners by requiring Instituto per la <ORGANIZATION> Ricostruzione </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industriale </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of `` white knight'' <ORGANIZATION> Banca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerciale </ORGANIZATION>, to apply separately to the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IRI </ORGANIZATION>, which balked at the idea, is controlled by the Italian government and accounts for about a quarter of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s gross national product. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Falise </PERSON>, who says he was forced to devote all his time to the takeover fight, said <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> is negotiating with `` several'' foreign and domestic banks about a possible merger. However, analysts say if an offer happens to emerge it must be extremely attractive to win over shareholders at this late date. <ORGANIZATION> Banca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerciale </ORGANIZATION> had offered $ 84 a share for 51 percent of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s approximately 18 million common shares outstanding before withdrawing its bid. The merger proposal was part of a complex defensive restructuring plan that included sale of Irving assets, cost-cutting measures and a special cash dividend. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, which owns about 4.9 percent of <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION>, is offering $ 15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its own stock for each of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s roughly 18 million common shares outstanding. <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> maintains his bid is just as attracive now as it was a year ago, although the cash portion has declined significantly. If he had to do things over again, he'd still bid for <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> said. `` We would n't have stuck with it that long unless we felt that way,'' he said. `` It gets a little frustrating. You have to have a lot of patience.''
