<HEAD>London Stocks Close Lower in Moderate Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices fell on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Thursday in modest trading, with activity again focused on takeover rumors following Wednesday's bid for <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>, which would be the largest ever takeover of a British company. Consolidated Gold Fields' shares, whose sharp gains Wednesday helped pull the entire market higher, were depressed Thursday as excitement subsided over <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>'s 2.9 billion-pound, or $ 4.8 billion, bid. But takeover speculation in half a dozen other stocks, sparked by the move on <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION>, buoyed the market against an otherwise bearish tone. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed 8.1 points, or 0.5 percent, lower at 1,788.7. Volume dropped to 393.6 million shares from 438.6 million shares Wednesday. Overall, losers among the market's 100 leading shares far outnumbered gainers, 61 to 22. The declines mirrored the mood on Wall Street, though late in the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> day the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average recovered and pushed to a slight advance. Consolidated Gold Fields ended 55 pence lower at 13.45 pounds, a relatively modest retreat after its 322-pence gain Wednesday.
