<HEAD>With PM-TWA-Consumers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senators Say Deregulation a Bad Thing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Several senators today criticized airline deregulation and the rash of mergers it has spawned, complaining they have given large air carriers monopoly power in some parts of the country and resulted in higher fares but less service. `` Simply stated, people are paying more to fly today because the airlines have developed monopoly hubs,'' declared Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He complained that a fare from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, was $ 120 in 1977, before airline deregulation, but that recently he paid $ 510 for the same trip. But the committee at a hearing aimed at examining airline pricing practices were told by <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> that air travelers have benefited by the deregulation of the industry with average air fares declining 13 percent in the last decade. He attributed an average 8 percent increase in domestic air fares during the first six months of the year to increased costs for fuel, new aircraft and a number of government-required safety initiatives. As an example of competition benefiting air travelers, <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> cited a recent decision by <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> to offer a $ 39 off-season fare between the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Airline deregulation has resulted in `` a substantial improvement in overall competition'' to the benefit of the public, insisted <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION>. But the explanation did n't satisfy a number of the senators including <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>; Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., and Sen. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.D. </LOCATION>, who said fares and service to their parts of the country have suffered `` It's cheaper to fly across the nation than it is to fly across <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. That is a very bizarre situation,'' complained <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, who suggested `` some re-regulation'' would be in order that would require ticket prices to be linked to miles traveled. <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON> and <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, the ranking Repubican on the committee, also warned that airline fare and service practices could lead to some additional government controls on the industry. `` In certain airports competition does not exist. Airlines get a lock on an airport and when they get a lock they can do pretty much what they please,'' declared <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>. He cited <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> dominance at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> where the airline controls 83 percent of the flights since its merger two years ago with <ORGANIZATION> Ozark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION>, once its chief competitor. Single airlines also dominate at <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Burnley </LOCATION>, however, defended his department's approval of 21 airline mergers in recent years and maintained that even at the airports cited by the senators competition has been maintained. `` Not only has new entry -LRB- by airlines -RRB- occurred at each of these hubs, but competing incumbent carriers continue to provide competitive service,'' said <LOCATION> Burnley </LOCATION>. But when pressed by <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, <PERSON> Burnely </PERSON> said the department has been disappointed at the level of competition as <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>' <LOCATION> Lambert </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> since <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s merger with Ozark. He said the department had expected, for example, that <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> would move into the competitive void created by the TWA-Ozark merger with as many as 60 flights a day instead of the 22 or 23 flights a day it currently operates through <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` I'd like to know why that has occurred,'' said <LOCATION> Burnley </LOCATION>, promising the department would examine the competitive situation at the airport.
