<HEAD>Dollar Rises; Gold Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Tuesday to Wednesday in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained ground in quiet trading Thursday despite a bout of central bank intervention. Gold prices fell overseas but recovered somewhat in domestic dealings. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted bullion at $ 399 a troy ounce, up from $ 396.35 late Wednesday, when the metal slid below the $ 400-an-ounce level for the first time in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since early last year. Dealers attributed the rise in domestic gold prices to technical factors. Trading in currency markets was dull. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Discount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> intervened when the dollar topped 1.88 West German marks. Because the market was thin, `` it did n't take much to turn the dollar around,'' he said. Many dealers were waiting on the sidelines for Saturday's meeting of the leading industrialized democracies While no policy changes are expected to result from the Group of Seven gathering in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, a cloud of caution still hung over the markets. The G-7 nations include the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Trading the yen remained paralyzed due to the serious illness of Japanese Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>. `` When -LRB- he -RRB- dies, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> will shut down the markets for two days, and then it will be difficult to close on's yen positions,'' said a dealer at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose 0.29 Japanese yen to a closing 134.47 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it fell to 134.45 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to 134.69 yen from 134.29 yen on Wednesday. The dollar gained against the British pound. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> it cost $ 1.6675 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.6755 late Wednesday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.6702 to buy one pound, less expensive than Wednesday's $ 1.6738. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8763 West German marks, up from 1.8745; 1.5851 Swiss francs, up from 1.5820; 6.3860 French francs, up from 6.3650; 1,399.25 Italian lire, up from 1.395.75, and 1.2187 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2159. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8790 West German marks, up from 1.8748; 1.5870 Swiss francs, up from 1.5833; 6.3955 French francs, up from 6.3710; 2.1150 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1145; 1,401.50 Italian lire, up from 1,395.60; 1.2188 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2183. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose to $ 399.30 a troy ounce from $ 398.40 on Wednesday. But gold prices in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> mirrored Wednesday's plunge in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, closing below the $ 400-an-ounce level. Traders in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> described the market as `` panicked and frenzied.'' Gold finished in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a late bid price of $ 397.75 a troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $ 401.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold dropped to a bid of $ 397, compared with $ 400.50 late Wednesday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 2.96 to close at a bid $ 402.42. Silver for current delivery finished at $ 6.250 a troy ounce on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comex </ORGANIZATION>, up from $ 6.177 on Wednesday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the metal was quoted at a late bid price of $ 6.24 a troy ounce, compared with Wednesday's $ 6.22.
