ober at $ 400 a troy ounce; silver was 7.1 cents to 7.3 cents higher with September at $ 6.25 a troy ounce. Copper futures soared on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, resuming a month-long upward trend linked to tight supplies and growing demand, analysts said. Copper settled 1.8 cents to 3.05 cents higher with September at $ 1.1535, a new lifetime high for that contract. Frozen pork belly futures surged as much as 1.82 cents a pound on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in a technical rally in the absence of fresh supply-and-demand factors, analysts said. Hog futures were mostly higher in anticipation of a heavy weekend kill and cattle futures were mixed. The bearish effect of weaker cash cattle markets was offset by expectations for higher cash prices, analysts said. Live cattle settled .40 cent lower to .43 cent higher with October at 69.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .55 cent lower to .02 cent higher with September at 79.20 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .57 cent higher with October at 39.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .95 cent to 1.82 cents higher with February at 52.15 cents a pound. Oil futures prices ended mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the market awaited this weekend's <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> price committee meeting. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 9 cents higher with November at $ 14.65 a barrel; heating oil was .03 cent lower to .07 cent higher with October at 41.06 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .10 cent lower to .50 cent higher with October at 45.85 cents a gallon. Stock-index futures retreated on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </