<HEAD>Democrats Fail to Limit Debate on Higher Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to FIX to seven votes short, sted six</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> failed Thursday to break a Republican filibuster of a bill clouded in presidential politics to raise the $ 3.35 an hour minimum wage for the first time since 1981. On a 53-43 vote _ seven short of the 60 needed _ the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> refused to limit to 30 more hours debate on legislation by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., to raise the wage floor to $ 3.75 in January, $ 4.15 in 1990 and $ 4.55 in 1991 `` It's only clear that there is a deliberate attempt to stall action on this bill,'' said Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, who called the Republican tactics a Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, the leader of the Republican opposition to any increase in the minimum wage that does not include a subminimum wage for new hires, said the issue needs extended debate. `` I know a little bit about filibustering and I've certainly led my share around here,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. `` But I only lead them on very, very important issues where we really have to have extended debate or what I would call extended educational dialogue. This particular bill needs a lot of that.'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> a week ago introduced the first Republican amendment in the debate _ a 90-day, 80 percent subminimum wage applicable to all new hires. As a parlimentary tactic, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> immediately offered a substitute amendment slightly expanding a currently allowed but little used 85 percent subminimum wage for full-time students who work no more than 20 hours a week. Since then, there have been no votes in five days of debate. Under the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s rules, approval of <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s substitute would effectively kill what Republicans call a subminimum training wage that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> have coupled to their approval of any incease in the $ 3.35 wage floor. `` We're not going to get a fair hearing on the training wage because the labor leaders do n't want it,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. `` It's not the Republicans versus the Democrats; it's the Republicans versus the labor leaders. They're telling us we can take this or leave it; we're not going to play that game. <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said Republicans supporting the filibuster `` obviously know that the presidential nominee of their party, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, was n't serious when he told Americans he wanted an increase in the minimum wage.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has declined to specify in the past two weeks how a big an increase in the minimum wage he could support, saying any raise should be coupled to a subminimum training wage. His vice presidential running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, R-Ind., this week again mentioned a raise to $ 4 over two years, a proposal he submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> two months ago <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> scheduled a second cloture vote for Friday in an effort to break the logjam amid indications that some of the support for the filibuster may be waning. `` We may not be successful tomorrow, but we're going to try,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. Three Republicans _ Sens. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> _ joined 50 Democrats in Thursday's vote to end the filibuster. Three Democrats _ Sens. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> _ joined Republians in voting to allow it to continue. `` It's an open secret in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> that the White House has asked the Republicans to vote in favor of a filibuster,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` And the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> has asked them to keep on voting for a filibuster tomorrow and next week.'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and other supporters of a minimum wage increase say it would only restore the 30 percent loss of purchasing power that inflation has taken away from workers on that `` bottom rung'' since it was last raised in 1981. Proponents said the raise will directly benfit some 15 million workers now paid below $ 4.55 an hour. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, however, said only about 2 million of the minimum wage earners are what he called `` working poor'' heads of households. `` The minimum wage really is irrelvevant except that by pushing up the bottom some 38 percent ... every other wage scale in the country has to go up correspondingly, and the cost of every good and service in this country has to go up correspondingly,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimates that raising the minimum wage would increase the rate of inflation by 0.2 to 0.3 percentage points a year. Inflation so far the first eight months of 1988 is running at 4.6 percent.
